\begin_layout Standard
The BFM equations are written following the notation proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "vichi07_part1"

\end_inset

, which is briefly summarized in this section.
 The reader is referred to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "vichi07_part1"

\end_inset

 for a more theoretical viewpoint on the extension of the ERSEM approach
 to the system state variables of the plankton ecosystem.
 As shown in Tab.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:model_variables"

\end_inset

, each variable is mathematically expressed by a multi-dimensional array
 that contains the concentrations of reference chemical constituents.
 We use a superscript indicating the CFF for a specific living functional
 group and a subscript for the basic constituent.
 For instance, diatoms are LFG of producers and comprise 6 living CFFs written
 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{i}^{(1)}\equiv\left(P_{c}^{(1)},P_{n}^{(1)},P_{p}^{(1)},P_{s}^{(1)},P_{f}^{(1)},P_{l}^{(1)}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The standard model resolves 4 different groups for phytoplankton 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{(j)},\,j=1,2,3,4$
\end_inset

 (diatoms, autotrophic nanoflagellates, picophytoplankton and large phytoplankto
n), 4 for zooplankton 
\begin_inset Formula $Z^{(j)},\,j=3,4,5,6$
\end_inset

 (carnivorous and omnivorous mesozooplankton, microzooplankton and heterotrophic
 nanoflagellates), 1 for bacteria, 7 inorganic variables for nutrients and
 gases (phosphate, nitrate, ammonium, silicate, reduction equivalents, oxygen,
 carbon dioxide) and 10 organic non-living components for dissolved and
 particulate detritus (cf..
 Tab.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:model_variables"

\end_inset

 and Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Scheme-Pelagic"

\end_inset

).
 The state variable nitrate is assumed here to be the sum of both nitrate
 and nitrite.
 Reduction equivalents represent all the reduced ions produced under anaerobic
 conditions.
 This variable was originally used only in the benthic nutrient regeneration
 module of ERSEM 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ruardij95a"

\end_inset

 but was extended to the water column in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "vichi04"

\end_inset

.
 In this  approach, all the nutrient-carbon and chlorophyll-carbon ratios
  are allowed to vary within their given ranges and each component has a
 distinct biological time rate of change.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "vichi07_part1"

\end_inset

 the dynamical equations are written in two forms: 1) rates of change form;
 and 2) explicit functional form.
 In 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rates of change form
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, the biogeochemical reaction term a generic state variable 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is written as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{dC}{dt}\right|_{bio}=\sum_{i=1,n}\sum_{j=1,m}\left.\frac{dC}{dt}\right|_{V_{i}}^{e_{j}},\label{eq:fluxes_form}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where the right hand side contains the terms representing significant processes
 for each living or non-living component.
 The superscripts 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{j}$
\end_inset

 are the abbreviations indicating the process which determines the variation.
 In Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:abbreviations"

\end_inset

 we report the acronyms of the processes used in the superscripts.
 The subscripts 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}$
\end_inset

 indicate the state variable involved in the process.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $V=C$
\end_inset

, we refer to intra-group interactions such as cannibalism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a term is present as a source in one equation and as a sink in another,
 we refer to it following this equivalent notation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{dC}{dt}\right|_{V}^{e}=-\left.\frac{dV}{dt}\right|_{C}^{e}.\label{eq:flip_flop_rule}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\shape italic
\emph on

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

functional process form
\shape default
\emph default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, the formulation of the dynamic dependencies on other variables is made
 explicit, 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default
: all the rates of change in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fluxes_form"

\end_inset

) are given in the complete functional parameterization.
 Although this is the more complete mathematical form, it is more difficult
 to read and interpret at a glance, especially when trying to distinguish
 which processes affect the dynamics of which variable .
 All equations in this Part will be presented both in rate of change and
 in functional process forms.
