\begin_layout Standard
Primary producers are divided in four principal sub-groups coarsely representing
 the functional spectrum of phytoplankton in marine systems.
 The operational model definitions of the phytoplankton groups are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
diatoms (
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}^{(1)}$
\end_inset

), ESD = 20-200
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, unicellular eukaryotes enclosed by a silica frustule eaten by micro- and
 mesozooplankton;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
autotrophic nanoflagellates (
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}^{(2)}$
\end_inset

), ESD = 2-20
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, motile unicellular eukaryotes comprising smaller dinoflagellates and other
 autotrophic microplanktonic flagellates eaten by heterotrophic nanoflagellates,
 micro- and mesozooplankton;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
picophytoplankton (
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}^{(3)}$
\end_inset

), ESD = 0.2-2
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, prokaryotic organism generally indicated as non-diazotrophic autotrophic
 bacteria such as 
\emph on
Prochlorococcus
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
Synechococcus
\emph default
, but also mixed eukaryotic species 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "worden04"

\end_inset

, mostly preyed by heterotrophic nanoflagellates;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
large, slow-growing phytoplankton (
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}^{(4)}$
\end_inset

), ESD > 100
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, that represents a wide group of phytoplankton species, also comprising
 larger species belonging to the previous groups (for instance dinoflagellates)
 but also those that during some period of the year develop a form of (chemo)def
ense to predator attack.
 This group generally has low growth rates and small food matrix values
 with respect to micro- and mesozooplankton groups.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The processes parameterized in the biological source term are gross primary
 production (
\emph on
gpp
\emph default
