\begin_layout Subsection
Photosynthesis and carbon dynamics
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Photosynthesis-and-carbon"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Photosynthesis is primarily controlled by light by means of the non-dimensional
 light regulation factor proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "jassby76"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{P}^{E}=1-\exp\left(-\frac{E_{PAR}}{E_{K}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{K}$
\end_inset

 is the optimal irradiance, defined as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
E_{k} & = & P_{m}^{*}/\alpha^{*}\nonumber \\
P_{m}^{*} & = & f_{P}^{T}\,f_{P}^{PP}\,r_{P}^{0}\,\frac{P_{c}}{P_{l}}\label{eq:phytoplankton_Ek}\\
\alpha^{*} & = & f_{P}^{T}\,f_{P}^{PP}\alpha_{chl}^{0}\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The maximum chl-specific photosynthetic rate 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{m}^{*}$
\end_inset

 is controlled by the non-storable nutrients that control primary production
 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{P}^{PP}$
\end_inset

 (Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Multiple-nutrient-limitation"

\end_inset

).
 It is assumed that both 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{m}^{*}$
\end_inset

 are controlled by the same regulating factors 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "jassby76,behrenfeld04"

\end_inset

.
 When instantaneous light is used, the equation is written in the following
 form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{P}^{E}=1-\exp\left(-\frac{\alpha_{chl}^{0}E_{PAR}P_{l}}{r_{P}^{0}P_{c}}\right)\label{eq:light-regfac}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

while in case the length of the photoperiod is considered, this is implicitly
 done in 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{m}^{*}$
\end_inset

 that becomes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{m}^{*}=f_{P}^{T}\,f_{P}^{PP}\,r_{P}^{0}\,\frac{P_{c}}{P_{l}}\frac{\Phi}{24}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 is the daylight length in hours 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "lazzari12"

\end_inset

.
 The final form of gross primary production also depends on the choice of
 the daylight availability.
 In the case of instantaneous or average daily irradiance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "vichi07_part2"

\end_inset

, it is written as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{dP_{c}}{dt}\right|_{O^{(3)}}^{gpp}=f_{P}^{T}f_{P}^{E}f_{P}^{PP}\,r_{P}^{0}P_{c}.\label{eq:phytoplankton_gpp}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that it is possible to further control temperature limitation with
 a cut-off value 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{P}^{T}$
\end_inset

 applied to the temperature regulating factor as done in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "vichi07_part2"

\end_inset

 to control the growth of picophytoplankton at high latitudes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f^{T}=\max\left(0,\,f^{T}-c_{P}^{T}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Respiration is defined as the sum of the basal respiration, which is independent
 of the production rate, and the activity respiration:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{dP_{c}}{dt}\right|_{O^{(3)}}^{rsp}=b_{P}f_{P}^{T}P_{c}+\gamma_{P}\left.\frac{dP_{c}}{dt}\right|_{O^{(3)}}^{gpp}.\label{eq:phytoplankton_rsp}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Basal respiration is only a function of the carbon biomass, temperature
 (through the regulating factor 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{_{P}}^{T}$
\end_inset

) and the specific constant rate 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{_{P}}$
\end_inset

.
 The activity respiration is a constant fraction (
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{_{P}}$
\end_inset

) of the total gross primary production.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The term lysis includes all the non-resolved mortality processes that disrupt
 the cell membrane, such as mechanical causes, virus and yeasts.
 It is assumed that the lysis rate is partitioned between particulate and
 dissolved detritus and tends towards the maximum specific rate 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{P}^{0}$
\end_inset

 with a saturation function of the nutrient stress as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\NSP\left.\frac{dP_{c}}{dt}\right|_{R_{c}^{(6)}}^{lys} & \NSP= & \NSP\varepsilon_{P}^{^{n,p}}\left(\frac{h_{P}^{p,n}}{f_{P}^{p,n}+h_{P}^{p,n}}d_{P}^{0}P_{c}+\chi^{lys}\right)\label{eq:phytoplankton_lys_R6}\\
\NSP\left.\frac{dP_{c}}{dt}\right|_{R_{c}^{(1)}}^{lys} & \NSP= & \NSP\left(1-\varepsilon_{P}^{^{n,p}}\right)\label{eq:phytoplankton_lys_R1}\\
 &  & \left(\frac{h_{P}^{p,n}}{f_{P}^{p,n}+h_{P}^{p,n}}d_{P}^{0}P_{c}+\chi^{lys}\right)\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The lysis of cells generates both dissolved and particulate detritus; the
 structural parts of the cell are not as easily degradable as the cytoplasm,
 therefore the percentage going to DOC is inversely proportional to the
 internal nutrient content and constrained by the minimum structural content
 in the following way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varepsilon_{_{P}}^{^{n,p}}=\min\left(1,\frac{p_{_{P}}^{min}}{P_{p}/P_{c}},\frac{n_{_{P}}^{min}}{P_{n}/P_{c}}\right).\label{eq:phytoplankton_lys_partition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 This equation ensures that the carbon and nutrients in the supportive structure
s, which are assumed to have 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{P}^{min}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{P}^{min}$
\end_inset

 nutrient ratios, are always released as particulate components.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model also implements and extra lysis rate in the last term of eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:phytoplankton_lys_R6"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:phytoplankton_lys_R1"

\end_inset

), which is dependent on the population density.
 This term is controlled by an optional specific lysis rate 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\chi^{lys}=d_{P}^{x}\frac{P_{c}}{P_{c}+h_{P}^{x}}P_{c}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is usually included for those phytoplankton population that are indedible
 and therefore acts as an additional mortality term to regulate the population
 dynamics.
\end_layout

