Multiple nutrient limitation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Multiple-nutrient-limitation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The BFM inherits the treatment of nutrient limitation from the original
 work by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "barettabekker97"

\end_inset

 which has similarities to the Caperon and Meyer equation, with some specific
 extensions.
 Nutrients are divided in two main groups, the ones that directly control
 carbon phosynthesis (as silicate, since duplication can only occur with
 Si deposition) and the ones that are decoupled from carbon uptake because
 of the existence of cellular storage capabilities.
 Limiting factors for nutrients can be both internal (i.e.
 based on the internal nutrient quota) or external (based on dissolved inorganic
 concentration).
 The internal limitation is only partly based on 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "droop73"

\end_inset

, with the concepts of nutrient surge and storage by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "barettabekker97"

\end_inset

 and the possibility to apply the parameterization of net growth described
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "vichi04"

\end_inset

 by means of the parameter 
\family typewriter
p_netgrowth
\family default
 in the namelist (Tab.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:phytoplankton_parameters"

\end_inset

).
 The regulating factors for internal limitation are controlled by the optimal
 and minimum values for the existence of structural components (
\begin_inset Formula $n_{P}^{opt},n_{_{P}}^{\min}$
\end_inset

), and they are implemented for N, P and Fe (Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Iron-in-phytoplankton"

\end_inset

) and also for Si 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "lazzari12"

\end_inset

, although in this case it is not possible to have luxury uptake because
 there is no storage for dissolved silicate in the cell:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{P}^{n}=\min\left(1,\max\left(0,\frac{P_{n}/P_{c}-n_{P}^{min}}{n_{P}^{opt}-n_{P}^{min}}\right)\right)\label{eq:phytoplankton_regfac-N}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{P}^{p}=\min\left(1,\max\left(0,\frac{P_{p}/P_{c}-p_{P}^{min}}{p_{P}^{opt}-p_{P}^{min}}\right)\right)\label{eq:phytoplankton_regfac-P}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{_{P}}^{f}=\frac{P_{f}/P_{c}-\phi_{P}^{min}}{\phi_{P}^{opt}-\phi_{P}^{min}}\label{eq:phytoplankton_Fe_regfac}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{f}_{_{P}}^{s}=\frac{P_{s}/P_{c}-s_{_{P}}^{\min}}{s_{_{P}}^{opt}-s_{_{P}}^{\min}}\label{eq:phytoplankton_regfac-Si-int}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{P}^{p}=\min\left(1,\max\left(0,\frac{P_{p}/P_{c}-p_{P}^{min}}{p_{P}^{opt}-p_{P}^{min}}\right)\right)\label{eq:phytoplankton_P_regfac}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that the ratios between brackets can be larger than 1 because the nutrient
 quota are allowed to reach the maximum values (cf.
 Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Nutrient-uptake"

\end_inset

) but the regulating factor has to be limited to 1 because above the optimal
 quotum there is no limitation to physiological processes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a flag (Tab.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:phytoplankton_parameters"

\end_inset

) for the choice of external and internal silicon limitation in case of
 diatoms.
 External dissolved silicate control should be preferable 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "flynn03"

\end_inset

 and it implements a Monod regulation with variable half-saturation constant
 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{P}^{s}$
\end_inset

, modified according to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "contois59"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
f_{P^{(1)}}^{s} & = & \frac{N^{(5)}}{N^{(5)}+(h_{_{P}}^{s}+\varrho_{P}^{s}P_{s}^{(1)})}\label{eq:phytoplankton_Si_regfac-1}\\
f_{P^{(j)}}^{s} & = & 1,\quad j\neq1\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The Contois formulation implements a control on dissolved nutrient uptake
 that is dependent on the size of the population, in this case it is applied
 to biogenic silica as suggested by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "tsiaras08"

\end_inset

.
 If the Contois parameter is zero a classical Monod function is obtained,
 while if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varrho_{P}^{s}\neq0$
\end_inset

 the half-saturation constant is increased and the resulting silicate control
 factor is smaller.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multiple nutrient limitation is different for nutrients that can be stored
 in the cell and nutrients that cannot.
 The threshold combination (Liebig-like) is usually preferred to the multiplicat
ive approach 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "flynn03"

\end_inset

: the BFM allows the three alternative ways implemented in ERSEM-II to combine
 N and P limitation (that can be selected differently for each phytoplankton
 group, Tab.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:phytoplankton_parameters"

\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
f_{_{P}}^{n,p} & = & \min\left(f_{P}^{n},f_{P}^{p}\right)\label{eq:phytoplankton_regfac}\\
f_{_{P}}^{n,p} & = & \frac{2}{1/f_{P}^{n}+1/f_{P}^{p}}\\
f_{_{P}}^{n,p} & = & \sqrt{f_{P}^{n}f_{P}^{p}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

and a simple multiplicative approach for the effect of nutrients that directly
 control photosynthesis (eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:phytoplankton_gpp"

\end_inset

), such as 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{PP}=\hat{f}_{_{P}}^{s}$
\end_inset

 as done by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "lazzari12"

\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{PP}=f_{P}^{f}f_{P}^{s}$
\end_inset

 when iron dynamics is included (Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:iron_parameters"

\end_inset

) as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "vichi07_part1"

\end_inset

.
 The co-limitation from all nutrients is always done with a threshold method
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{_{P}}^{nut}=\min\left(f_{_{P}}^{n,p},f_{_{P}}^{f},f_{_{P}}^{s}\right)\label{eq:phytoplankton_allnut_regfac}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and it is considered in the parameterization of some processes such as chlorophy
ll synthesis and sinking (Secs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Chlorophyll-synthesis-acclimation"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Phytoplankton-sinking"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Nutrient uptake
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Nutrient-uptake"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A major problem in modelling nutrient uptake is to deal with unbalanced
 growth conditions, and any realistic application is expected to produce
 transient environmental conditions resulting in uncoupled assimilation
 rates of carbon and nutrients.
 The Droop (intracellular quota approach) and Monod (external concentration
 approach) equations produce consistent results when applied in balanced
 growth conditions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "morel87"

\end_inset

.
 The BFM approach, largely derived from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "barettabekker97"

\end_inset

, combines both mechanisms with a threshold control.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Nitrogen
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The uptake of DIN is the sum of the uptake of dissolved nitrate and ammonium
 and is the minimum between a diffusion-dependent uptake rate (when internal
 nutrient quota are low and nutrients are only structural), and a rate based
 on considerations of balanced growth and luxury uptake:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{flalign}
\sum_{j=3,4}\left.\frac{dP_{n}}{dt}\right|_{N^{(j)}}^{upt}=\nonumber \\
 & \NSP\NSP\NSP\NSP\NSP\NSP\min\left(\left(a_{P}^{n}\frac{h_{P}^{n}}{h_{P}^{n}+N^{(4)}}N^{(3)}+a_{P}^{n}N^{(4)}\right)P_{c},\right.\nonumber \\
 & \NSP\NSP\NSP\NSP\left.n_{_{P}}^{opt}G_{P}+\nu_{P}\left(n_{_{P}}^{\max}-\frac{P_{n}}{P_{c}}\right)P_{c}\right)\label{eq:phytoplankton_upt_N}
\end{flalign}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A preference for ammonium is parameterized through a saturation function
 that modulates the affinity constant for dissolved nitrate.
 Balanced uptake is a function of the net primary production 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{p}$
\end_inset

, which is computed as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G_{P}=\max\left(0,\left.\frac{dP_{c}}{dt}\right|_{O^{(3)}}^{gpp}\NSP-\left.\frac{dP_{c}}{dt}\right|_{R_{c}^{(i)}}^{exu}\NSP-\left.\frac{dP_{c}}{dt}\right|_{O^{(3)}}^{rsp}\NSP-\left.\frac{dP_{c}}{dt}\right|_{R_{c}^{(i)}}^{lys}\right)\label{eq:phytoplankton_net_growth}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nu_{P}=\max\left(0.05,\frac{G_{P}}{P_{c}}\right).
\]

\end_inset

When the nitrogen uptake rate in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:phytoplankton_upt_N"

\end_inset

) is positive, the partitioning between 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{(3)}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{(4)}$
\end_inset

uptake is done by multiplying the rate by the fractions: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varepsilon_{P}^{(3)}=\frac{a_{P}^{n}\frac{h_{P}^{n}}{h_{P}^{n}+N^{(4)}}N^{(3)}}{a_{P}^{n}N^{(4)}+a_{P}^{n}\frac{h_{P}^{n}}{h_{P}^{n}+N^{(4)}}N^{(3)}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varepsilon_{P}^{(4)}=\frac{a_{P}^{n}N^{(4)}}{a_{P}^{n}N^{(4)}+a_{P}^{n}\frac{h_{P}^{n}}{h_{P}^{n}+N^{(4)}}N^{(3)}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 When it is negative, the whole flux is directed to the DON pool 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{n}^{(1)}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Phosphorus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Phosphate uptake is simpler than N uptake as one single species is considered:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left.\frac{dP_{p}}{dt}\right|_{N^{(1)}}^{upt} & =\min\left(a_{P}^{(1)}N^{(1)}P_{c},\,p_{P}^{opt}G_{P}+\right.\nonumber \\
 & \left.+\nu_{P}\left(p_{P}^{\max}-\frac{P_{p}}{P_{c}}\right)P_{c}\right)\label{eq:phytoplankton_upt_P}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Silicate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Silicate is not stored in the cell and therefore the uptake is directly
 proportional to the net carbon growth (see eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:phytoplankton_net_growth"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{dP_{s}}{dt}\right|_{N^{(5)}}^{upt}=s_{P}^{opt}G_{P}\label{eq:phytoplankton_upt_Si}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Nutrient loss associated with lysis
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Nutrient-loss-lysis"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nutrients in the cell are not evenly distributed between cytoplasm and structura
l parts.
 When the cell wall is disrupted, part of the nutrients are released as
 dissolved organic matter (the nutrients in the cytoplasm) and part as particula
te organic matter (the nutrients in the structural parts, such as the cell
 wall).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The redistribution of the cellular elements C, N and P over the excretion
 variables reflects the preferential remineralization of P and to a lesser
 extent of N, with respect to C.
 This parameter values are based on the ERSEM-II parameterizations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barettabekker97"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{dP_{p}}{dt}\right|_{R_{i}^{(6)}}^{lys}=\varepsilon_{P}^{i}\frac{h_{P}^{p,n}}{f_{P}^{p,n}+h_{P}^{p,n}}d_{P}^{0}P_{i}\quad i=n,p\label{eq:phytoplankton_lys_P}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{dP_{p}}{dt}\right|_{R_{i}^{(1)}}^{lys}=\left(1-\varepsilon_{P}^{i}\right)\frac{h_{P}^{p,n}}{f_{P}^{p,n}+h_{P}^{p,n}}d_{P}^{0}P_{i}\quad i=n,p
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the case of Si, the release is always in particulate form   and thus
 is a constant fraction of the particulate carbon lysis 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{dP_{s}^{(1)}}{dt}\right|_{R_{s}^{(6)}}^{lys}=s_{P}^{opt}\left.\frac{dP_{c}^{(1)}}{dt}\right|_{R_{c}^{(6)}}^{lys}\label{eq:phytoplankton_lys_Si}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Exudation of carbohydrates
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Exudation-of-carbohydrates"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case of intra-cellular nutrient shortage, not all photosynthesized
 carbon can be assimilated into biomass, and the non-assimilated part is
 released in the form of dissolved carbohydrates.
 The model considers three different types of DOC (Tab.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:model_variables"

\end_inset

) and phytoplankton excretion must be consistent with the bacteria parameterizat
ion (Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Bacterioplankton"

\end_inset

).
 Carbohydrates are excreted when phytoplankton cannot equilibrate the fixed
 C with sufficient nutrients to maintain the minimum quotum needed for the
 synthesis of new biomass.
 The choice of the parametrization for DOC exudation is controlled by the
 flag parameters 
\family typewriter
p_netgrowth
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
p_switchDOC
\family default
 in the phytoplankton namelist (Tab.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:phytoplankton_parameters"

\end_inset

), which can be set differently for each sub-group.
 There is a runtime check that controls the consistency between the two
 parameters.
 When the flag is false, the ERSEM-II parameterization 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barettabekker97"

\end_inset

 as implemented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "vichi07_part1"

\end_inset

 is used,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{dP_{c}}{dt}\right|_{R_{c}^{(1)}}^{exu}=\left[\beta_{_{P}}+\left(1-\beta_{_{P}}\right)\left(1-f_{_{P}}^{n,p}\right)\right]\left.\frac{dP_{c}}{dt}\right|_{O^{(3)}}^{gpp}\label{eq:phytoplankton_exu}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where exudation (and thus carbon biomass loss) increases when phytoplankton
 has low nutrient:carbon ratios.
 The nutrient-stress excretion can also be partly directed to semi-refractory
 DOC (
\begin_inset Formula $R_{c}^{(2)}$
\end_inset

) by setting the parameter 
\family typewriter
p_switchDOC=3
\family default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left.\frac{dP_{c}}{dt}\right|_{R_{c}^{(1)}}^{exu} & = & \beta_{_{P}}\left.\frac{dP_{c}}{dt}\right|_{O^{(3)}}^{gpp}\\
\left.\frac{dP_{c}}{dt}\right|_{R_{c}^{(2)}}^{exu} & = & \left(1-\beta_{_{P}}\right)\left(1-f_{_{P}}^{n,p}\right)\left.\frac{dP_{c}}{dt}\right|_{O^{(3)}}^{gpp}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

 However, the ERSEM-II parameterization not only leads to the desired extra
 release of C-enriched DOM but also to a decrease of the population biomass.
 It has been shown by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "vichi04"

\end_inset

 that the use of a different parameterization results in the maintenance
 of higher standing stocks in the post bloom period with a consequently
 enhanced consumption of the non-limiting nutrients.
 This parameterization is also used by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "lazzari12"

\end_inset

 to allow the consumption of N species in a P-depleted environment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the 
\family typewriter
p_netgrowth
\family default
 flag is true, total exudation is directed to the state variable 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{c}^{(2)}$
\end_inset

 (see also Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Bacterioplankton"

\end_inset

 for a detailed explanation of DOM in the BFM), and it is written as the
 sum of an activity exudation linked to the gross primary production and
 a balance term
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{dP_{c}}{dt}\right|_{R_{c}^{(2)}}^{exu}=\beta_{P}\left.\frac{dP_{c}}{dt}\right|_{O^{(3)}}^{gpp}+G_{P}-G_{P}^{bal}\label{eq:phytoplankton_exc_sug-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
G_{P}^{bal} & =\max\left(0,\min\left(G_{P},\,\frac{1}{n_{P}^{min}}\sum_{j=3,4}\left.\frac{dP_{n}}{dt}\right|_{N^{(j)}}^{upt},\,\right.\right.\label{eq:phytoplankton_balance}\\
 & \left.\left.\frac{1}{p_{P}^{min}}\left.\frac{dP_{p}}{dt}\right|_{N^{(1)}}^{upt}\right)\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

