\begin_layout Subsection
Chlorophyll synthesis and photoacclimation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Chlorophyll-synthesis-acclimation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The chlorophyll equation in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:phytoplankton_Chl"

\end_inset

) is composed of two terms.
 The first one is net chlorophyll synthesis, which is mostly derived from
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "geider96,geider97"

\end_inset

 with some adaptations, and the second one represents the losses due to
 grazing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Net chlorophyll synthesis is namely a function of acclimation to light condition
s, nutrient availability and turnover rate.
 The former process is taken into account by Geider's parameterization,
 while the latter is generally parameterized with different formulations,
 for instance by assuming a dependence on gross carbon uptake 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "geider97,blackford04"

\end_inset

 and/or on nitrogen assimilation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "geider98,flynn01"

\end_inset

.
 To integrate the variety of processes into our formulations, we consider
 three different parameterizations presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "box:phytoplankton_Chl_synthesis"

\end_inset

 that have been used in different applications of the BFM (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "vichi09"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "lazzari12"

\end_inset

, Clementi et al., in preparation).
 The synthesis part is rather similar as it is controlled by the dynamical
 chl:C ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{chl}$
\end_inset

 proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "geider97"

\end_inset

, which regulates the amount of chlorophyll in the cell according to a non-dimen
sional ratio between the realized photosynthetic rate in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:phytoplankton_gpp"

\end_inset

) and the maximum potential photosynthesis:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{chl}=\theta_{chl}^{0}\frac{\left.\frac{dP_{c}}{dt}\right|_{O^{(3)}}^{gpp}}{\alpha^{*}E_{PAR}P_{l}}\label{eq:chl-geider}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and multiplying by a maximum chl:C ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{chl}^{0}$
\end_inset

 which is different for each phytoplankton functional group (Tab.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:phytoplankton_parameters"

\end_inset

).
 The major difference in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:chlsyn_OGS"

\end_inset

) proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "lazzari12"

\end_inset

 is the presence of the combined nutrient regulating factor, which implies
 that chl synthesis is reduced in regions limited by phosphorus like for
 instance the Mediterranean.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following the notation shown in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:phytoplankton_Ek"

\end_inset

, Geider's original  formulation is rewritten after some algebra as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{chl}=\theta_{chl}^{0}\,\frac{f_{P}^{E}r_{P}^{0}P_{c}}{\alpha_{chl}^{0}\,E_{PAR}P_{l}}\label{eq:chl-rho}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The ratio is down-regulated when the rate of light absorption (governed
 by the quantum efficiency and the amount of light-harvesting pigments)
 exceeds the rate of utilization of photons for carbon fixation, as explained
 in detail in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "geider96"

\end_inset

.
 Also here it is assumed that both 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{m}^{*}$
\end_inset

 are controlled by the same regulating factors 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "jassby76,behrenfeld04"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formulation of the lysis term is still unknown and this is reflected
 in the diversity of parameterizations that are available in the model and
 controlled by the namelist parameter 
\family typewriter
p_switchChl
\family default
 (Tab.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:phytoplankton_parameters"

\end_inset

).
 The user should consider the different assumptions and use them accordingly.
 A different parameterization can be used for each phytoplankton group to
 allow their testing.
 In eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:chlsyn_PELAGOS"

\end_inset

) it is assumed that chl lysis is simply linked to the carbon term, while
 in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:chlsyn_OGS"

\end_inset

) there is a relaxation to the optimal chl:C ratio with an additional lysis
 term linked to background mortality.
 The parameterization proposed in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:chlsyn_UNIBO"

\end_inset

) is slightly more elaborated as it considers an optimal cell acclimation
 to light that corresponds to an optimal value 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{PAR}/E_{K}=\epsilon^{opt}$
\end_inset

 of the exponential in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:light-regfac"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The theoretical chlorophyll concentration corresponding to optimal light
 acclimation in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:chlsyn_UNIBO"

\end_inset

) is computed as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{r_{P}^{0}P_{c}}{P_{l}^{opt}\alpha_{chl}^{0}} & = & \frac{E_{PAR}}{\epsilon^{opt}}\nonumber \\
P_{l}^{opt} & = & \epsilon^{opt}\frac{r_{P}^{0}P_{c}}{\alpha_{chl}^{0}\,E_{PAR}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

and the chl content in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:chlsyn_UNIBO"

\end_inset

) is relaxed to this optimal value with a specific time scale parameter
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{chl}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parameterization presented in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:chlsyn_NIOZ"

\end_inset

) has instead an explicit term for the turn-over rate of chl, 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{P}^{chl}$
\end_inset

.
 The losses of chlorophyll are not considered as mass losses in the model
 because we have currently not implemented a chl component in detritus and
 dissolved organic matter.
 The same consideration applies to the ingested chl fraction in zooplankton.
 All these terms are presently collected into a generic sink term  used
 for mass conservation purposes, which can be easily split into its major
 components once it is deemed necessary to follow the degradation products
 of chl (phaeopigments).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Light limitation and photoacclimation based on optimal light
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Light-limitation-and-optimal-light"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This parameterization is alternative to the one above and is consistent
 with the one originally implemented in ERSEM-II 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ebenhoeh97"

\end_inset

.
 It assumes that phytoplankton is acclimated to the prevailing light in
 a few days and that the C:chl ratio is constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The state variable 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{opt}$
\end_inset

 in the original ERSEM-II formulation  represented the light intensity at
 which production saturated for the whole phytoplankton community.
 We consider here an optimal light for each phytoplankton group indicated
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}_{l}^{(j)}$
\end_inset

, which has the same meaning as the light saturation parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{k}$
\end_inset

 used in the alternative formulation of chlorophyll dynamics (Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:phytoplankton_Ek"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A note of caution on the application of this parameterization: the model
 was formulated to simulate the daily production, therefore it is suggested
 to apply it with the daylight-averaged irradiance, possibly modulated by
 the duration of the daylight period (see Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:The-environmental-parameters"

\end_inset

).
 Several forms of the P-E curve are available:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
prod=f_{P}^{T}f_{P}^{s}r_{0P}\min\left(1,\frac{E_{PAR}}{\hat{P_{l}}}\right)\quad\textrm{(ramp)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
prod=f_{P}^{T}f_{P}^{s}r_{0P}\,\frac{E_{PAR}}{\hat{P_{l}}}\,e^{1-\frac{E_{PAR}}{\hat{P_{l}}}}\quad\textrm{(Steele)}
\]

\end_inset

The light regulating factor is computed by integrating the P-E curve over
 the depth of the considered layer, therefore the irradiance at the top
 of the layer  is used
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{_{P}}^{E}=\frac{1}{f_{P}^{T}f_{P}^{s}r_{0P}D}\int_{-D}^{0}prod\left(\frac{E_{_{PAR}}}{\hat{P_{l}}}\right)\;dz\label{eq:phytoplankton_f(I)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The time rate of change of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P_{l}}$
\end_inset

 is computed with a relaxation term
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{d\hat{P_{l}}}{dt}\right|_{bio}=\nu_{P}^{I}\left(E_{P}^{^{opt}}-\hat{P_{l}}\right)\label{eq:light_adaptation_bio}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{P}^{^{opt}}$
\end_inset

 is the reference light saturation parameter to which the phytoplankton
 adapt with frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{P}^{I}$
\end_inset

 (generally 4 days for a full acclimation).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The irradiance level to which phytoplankton may adapt is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{P}^{^{opt}}=\min\left(E_{P}^{max},\,\max\left(E_{P}^{min},\,E_{PAR}\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

which is a constrained ramp function over the  range of  saturating irradiance.
\end_layout

