\begin_layout Subsection
Iron in phytoplankton
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Iron-in-phytoplankton"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The iron (Fe) constituent in phytoplankton shown in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:phytoplankton_Fe"

\end_inset

) is not activated by default in the model.
 It is available as a compilation key 
\family typewriter
INCLUDE_PELFE
\family default
 and implements the iron dynamics proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "vichi07_part1"

\end_inset

 described by the parameters of Tab.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:iron_parameters"

\end_inset

.
 The iron cycle involves phytoplankton, particulate and dissolved component
 (Sec.
 ), while the zooplankton and bacteria fraction is neglected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:phytoplankton_Fe"

\end_inset

) for iron in phytoplankton 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{f}$
\end_inset

 contains a term for the uptake of Fe, a loss term related to turnover/cell
 lysis and a predation term.
 Similarly to N and P content, intracellular Fe:C quota are allowed to vary
 between a maximum and a minimum thresholds (
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{P}^{max}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{P}^{min}$
\end_inset

, Tab.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:iron_parameters"

\end_inset

), and the realized quotum is used to derive a non-dimensional regulating
 factor as in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:phytoplankton_regfac"

\end_inset

).
 The allowed minimum ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{P}^{min}$
\end_inset

 represents the evolutive adaptation of each functional group at the prevailing
 iron concentrations, and the optimal value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{P}^{opt}$
\end_inset

 indicates the cellular requirement for optimal growth.
 This regulating factor modulates the actual photosynthetic rate in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:phytoplankton_gpp"

\end_inset

), since there is a clear decrease in the activity of PSUs due to insufficient
 cellular Fe 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "sunda97"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The regulating factor inhibits carbon fixation, but iron can still be taken
 up in the cell, progressively increasing the internal quotum.
 Iron uptake from dissolved pools is computed as for N and P (Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Nutrient-uptake"

\end_inset

) by taking the minimum of two rates, a linear function of the ambient concentra
tion simulating the membrane through-flow at low external Fe concentration,
 and the balancing flux according to the carbon assimilation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\NSP\left.\frac{\partial P_{f}}{\partial t}\right|_{N^{(7)}}^{upt} & \NSP= & \NSP\min\left(a_{P}^{7}N^{(7)}P_{c},\,\phi_{_{P}}^{opt}G_{P}+\right.\label{eq:phytoplankton_upt_Fe}\\
 &  & \left.+f_{_{P}}^{T}r_{_{P}}^{0}\left(\phi_{_{P}}^{max}-\frac{P_{f}}{P_{c}}\right)P_{c}\right)\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

It is assumed that the only physiological iron loss from phytoplankton is
 linked to cell disruption, computed according to carbon lysis and assuming
 that particulate material has the minimum structural Fe:C ratio:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{\partial P_{f}}{\partial t}\right|_{R_{f}^{(6)}}^{lys}=\phi_{P}^{min}\left.\frac{\partial P_{c}}{\partial t}\right|_{R_{c}^{(6)}}^{lys}.\label{eq:phytoplankton_lys_Fe}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Phytoplankton sinking
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Phytoplankton-sinking"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sinking of biogenic material is a fundamental process for the simulation
 of carbon sequestration in the interior of the ocean.
 However, the estimation of the sinking velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{B}$
\end_inset

 is still parameterized in a very simplified way in the model.
 Any phytoplankton group is allowed to have a sinking velocity using the
 original ERSEM formulation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "varela95"

\end_inset

.
 This is generally valid only for diatoms, which reach their maximum velocity
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{^{sink}}$
\end_inset

 as a function of the total nutrient stress (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:phytoplankton_allnut_regfac"

\end_inset

) as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w_{_{P^{(1)}}}=\omega^{^{sink}}\max\left(0,\,l^{sink}-f_{_{P}}^{nut}\right)\label{eq:phytoplankton_sinking_velocity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $l^{sink}$
\end_inset

 is the nutrient regulating factor value below which the mechanism is effective.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Bacterioplankton
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Bacterioplankton"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bacterioplankton is included in the standard BFM with one single state variable
 representing a wide group of aerobic and anaerobic bacteria.
 The user can eventually expand the number of bacteria group using the modular
 facilities described in Part 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "part:BFM-code-description"

\end_inset

 of this document and by providing new dynamical equations in the code.
 The main source of carbon for bacterioplankton is the organic matter pool
 that is composed of particulate detritus (variables 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{(6)}$
\end_inset

) and dissolved organic matter (DOM, variables 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{(1)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{(2)}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to the original ERSEM parameterization 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barettabekker95"

\end_inset

 further expanded in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "vichi07_part1"

\end_inset

, the code contains also two alternative parameterizations proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "vichi04"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "polimene06"

\end_inset

.
 We will refer to BACT1 when indicating the standard most simple parameterizatio
n and to BACT2 and BACT3 for the
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "vichi04"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "polimene06"

\end_inset

 parameterizations, respectively.
 BACT1 set of equations is the default choice but all parameterizations
 are deemed equal and can be activated at run time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The different parameterizations consider that dissolved organic matter (DOM)
 available to pelagic bacteria may have different degrees of lability/refractivi
ty (see Tab.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:model_variables"

\end_inset

).
 The lability/refractivity characteristics of DOM are dependent on two factors:
 the C:N and C:P ratios of bacteria and the structure of organic molecules
 constituting the DOM matrix.
 DOM is assumed to be partitioned into three broad and distinct state variables,
 each of them corresponding to different degrees of lability/refractivity
 and having different production pathways.
 The parameterizations described below consider only one, two or all of
 the 3 classes.
 It is important to remark that the DOC fraction considered by the model
 covers only the labile and the semi-labile DOC part.
 Therefore, in the following we define, as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

semi-refractory
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the DOC fraction more slowly remineralized by bacteria only to avoid confusion
 with the truly refractory DOC (with turnover time of 100-1000 years) that
 is not considered at all in the model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most labile fraction of the total DOM pool 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{i}^{(1)},\,i=c,n,p$
\end_inset

 is produced by phytoplankton, zooplankton and bacteria via the lysis, mortality
 and sloppy feeding (mesozooplankton only) processes.
 This DOM variable is characterized by C:N and C:P ratios identical to those
 of the producing functional groups.
 The characteristic turnover time-scale is assumed to be 1 day.
 The semi-labile DOM fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{c}^{(2)}$
\end_inset

 is produced through excretion by phytoplankton and bacteria in order to
 achieve/maintain their internal 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

optimal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 stoichiometry (this part is considered only in BACT2 and BACT3 parameterization
s).
 The production process of semi-labile DOM can be thought as release of
 excess carbon and, therefore, negligible N and P pools are assumed.
 The characteristic turnover time-scale is assumed to be 10 days.
 DOM released by bacteria as capsular material 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{c}^{(3)}$
\end_inset

 is also introduced in BACT2 and BACT3, and it represents the semi-refractory
 fraction of the DOM, but it is only considered as a source of carbon in
 BACT3 
