\begin_layout Subsection
Regulating factors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The oxygen non dimensional regulating factor 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{B}^{o}$
\end_inset

 (eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bacteria_regfac_O"

\end_inset

) is parameterized with a type III control formulation as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{_{B}}^{o}=\frac{\left(O^{(2)}\right)^{3}}{\left(O^{(2)}\right)^{3}+\left(h_{_{B}}^{o}\right)^{3}}\label{eq:bacteria_regfac_O}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where the dissolved oxygen concentration 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{(2)}$
\end_inset

 is considered, and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{_{B}}^{o}$
\end_inset

 is the oxygen concentration at which metabolic functionalities are halved.
 This steep sigmoid has been proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "vichi04"

\end_inset

 to efficiently switch between bacteria metabolism under aerobic conditions
 and anaerobic metabolism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The non dimensional regulating factor based on the nutritional content of
 bacterial cells is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{_{B}}^{n,p}=\min\left(1,\,\frac{B_{p}/B_{c}}{p^{^{opt}}},\,\frac{B_{n}/B_{c}}{n^{^{opt}}}\right);\label{eq:bact_quota_regulation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $n_{B}^{opt}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{B}^{opt}$
\end_inset

 are the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

optimal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $N:C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P:C$
\end_inset

 bacterial internal quota 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "goldman78"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Respiration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The respiration sink term is composed of basal and activity respiration
 as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left.\frac{dB_{c}}{dt}\right|_{O^{(3)}}^{rsp} & =b_{_{B}}f_{B}^{T}B_{c}+\label{eq:bacteria_rsp}\\
 & \left[\gamma_{_{B}}^{a}+\gamma_{_{B}}^{o}\left(1-f_{B}^{o}\right)\right]\left.\sum_{j=1,2,6}\frac{dB_{c}}{dt}\right|_{R_{c}^{(j)}}^{upt}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The basal respiration is parameterized as for phytoplankton with a constant
 specific respiration rate 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{_{B}}$
\end_inset

 and the regulating factor for temperature given in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Q10"

\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{B}^{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{B}^{O}$
\end_inset

 are the fraction of production that is used for activity respiration under
 oxic and low oxygen conditions respectively.
 Since the BFM pelagic bacteria parameterization encompasses both aerobic
 and anaerobic bacterial activities, we consider here the differences in
 the energetics of the metabolic pathways in relation to oxygen availability.
 Anaerobic bacteria have a lower efficiency because they need to consume
 (respire) more carbon in order to produce the same amount of energy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Mortality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mortality (lysis) process is given by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left.\frac{dB_{c}}{dt}\right|_{R_{i}^{(1)}}^{lys} & =\left(d_{0_{B}}f_{B}^{T}+d_{_{B}}^{d}B_{c}\right)B_{c}\quad i=c,n,p\label{eq:bacteria_viral_lys}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{0_{B}}$
\end_inset

 is a temperature enhanced background mortality specific rate and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{_{B}}^{d}$
\end_inset

 is a density dependent mortality specific rate assumed to be dependent
 on virus infection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
BACT1 parameterization 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:BACT1"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this parameterization labile DOC (
\begin_inset Formula $R_{c,n,p}^{(1)}$
\end_inset

) is the only class of dissolved organic matter resolved by the model and,
 together with Particulate Organic Detritus (
\begin_inset Formula $R_{c,n,p}^{(6)}$
\end_inset

), constitute the organic substrate available to bacteria.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Substrate uptake 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total carbon uptake rate of organic substrate in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bacteria_C"

\end_inset

) is regulated by environmental factors and substrate availability with
 a threshold formulation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sum_{j=1,6}\left.\frac{dB_{c}}{dt}\right|_{R_{c}^{(j)}}^{upt} & =\min\left(f_{_{B}}^{n,p}f_{_{B}}^{T}r_{0_{B}}B_{c},\right.\label{eq:bacteria_bcd-1}\\
 & \NSP\NSP\NSP\left.\sum_{j=1,6}\nu_{B}^{R^{(j)}}f_{_{R^{(j)}}}^{n,p}R_{c}^{(j)}+\nu_{0_{B}}^{R^{(1)}}\left(1-f_{_{R^{(1)}}}^{n,p}\right)R_{c}^{(1)}\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0_{B}}$
\end_inset

 is the maximum potential specific growth rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{B}^{R^{(j)}}$
\end_inset

 is the specific quality-dependent uptake rate for substrate, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0_{B}}^{R^{(1)}}$
\end_inset

 is the specific, quality-independent uptake rate for semi-labile organic
 matter and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{_{R^{(j)}}}^{n,p}$
\end_inset

 is the non-dimensional regulating factor based on the of organic substrate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{_{R^{(j)}}}^{n,p}=\min\left(1,\,\frac{R_{p}^{(j)}/R_{c}^{(j)}}{p^{^{opt}}},\,\frac{R_{p}^{(j)}/R_{c}^{(j)}}{n^{^{opt}}}\right)\,j=1,6f_{_{R^{(j)}}}^{n,p}\label{eq:Bact_quota}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The uptake of the nutrient components in the dissolved and particulate fractions
 is then derived from the actual nutrient ratios in the organic matter as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{dB_{i}}{dt}\right|_{R_{i}^{(j)}}^{upt}=\frac{R_{i}^{(j)}}{R_{c}^{(j)}}\left.\frac{dB_{c}}{dt}\right|_{R_{c}^{(j)}}^{upt},\quad i=n,p;\,j=1,6\label{eq:subnut_upt}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Nutrient release and uptake
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:BACT1-Nutrient-release-uptake"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mineralizers/phytoplankton competitors behavior is controlled by the
 non-dimensional factors 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{_{B}}^{p}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{_{B}}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and by the specific relaxation rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{_{B}}^{p}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{_{B}}^{n}$
\end_inset

 towards the optimal internal quota.
 The process it involves only phosphate and ammonium components:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left.\frac{dB_{p}}{dt}\right|_{N^{(1)}}^{upt,rel} & \NSP= & \NSP f_{_{B}}^{p}\nu_{_{B}}^{p}\left\Vert \frac{B_{p}}{B_{c}}-p_{_{B}}^{^{opt}}\right\Vert B_{c}\label{eq:bacteria_upt/rel_P}\\
\left.\frac{dB_{n}}{dt}\right|_{N^{(4)}}^{upt,rel} & \NSP= & \NSP f_{_{B}}^{n}\nu_{_{B}}^{n}\left\Vert \frac{B_{n}}{B_{c}}-n_{_{B}}^{^{opt}}\right\Vert B_{c}\label{eq:bacteria_upt/rel_N}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{dB_{n}}{dt}\right|_{N^{(3)}}^{upt}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case of phosphorus as in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bacteria_upt/rel_P"

\end_inset

), for instance, if there is an excess of nutrients in the cell, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{B_{p}}{B_{c}}-p_{_{B}}^{^{opt}}>0$
\end_inset

, the non-dimensional parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{_{B}}^{p}=-1$
\end_inset

, and if 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{B_{p}}{B_{c}}-p_{_{B}}^{^{opt}}<0$
\end_inset

 there is direct uptake from the water as a function of the nutrient concentrati
on in a Michaelis-Menten form, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{_{B}}^{p}=\frac{N^{(1)}}{N^{(1)}+h_{_{B}}^{p}}$
\end_inset

 .
 The same applies to nitrogen, and the direct uptake is regulated by the
 factor 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{_{B}}^{n}=\frac{N^{(4)}}{N^{(4)}+h_{_{B}}^{n}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Excretion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this parameterization the release term appearing in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bacteria_C"

\end_inset

) is nil.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
BACT2 parameterization
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:BACT2"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this parameterization originally proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "vichi04"

\end_inset

, the substrate available for uptake is composed of 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{c,n,p}^{(1,6)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{c}^{(2)}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Substrate uptake 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{c}^{(1,6)}$
\end_inset

 uptake is parameterized as in BACT1 (see eq.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bacteria_bcd-1"

\end_inset

) and the 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{c}^{(2)}$
\end_inset

 uptake is added.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sum_{j=1,2,6}\left.\frac{dB_{c}}{dt}\right|_{R_{c}^{(j)}}^{upt} & =\min\left(f_{_{B}}^{n,p}f_{_{B}}^{T}r_{0_{B}}B_{c},\right.\label{eq:bacteria_bcd-2}\\
 & \BNSP\NSP\NSP\NSP\left.\sum_{j=1,6}\NSP\nu_{B}^{R^{(j)}}f_{_{R^{(j)}}}^{n,p}R_{c}^{(j)}+\nu_{0_{B}}^{R^{(1)}}\left(1-f_{_{R^{(1)}}}^{n,p}\right)R_{c}^{(1)}+\nu_{B}^{R^{(2)}}R_{c}^{(2)}\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{B}^{R^{(2)}}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{c}^{(2)}$
\end_inset

 specific uptake rate.
 The uptake of the nutrient components in the dissolved and particulate
 fractions is the same defined for BACT1 in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:subnut_upt"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Nutrient release and uptake
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The uptake dynamics is similar to the one for phytoplankton, with affinity
 constants for phosphate and ammonia 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\lang english
(
\begin_inset Formula $a1_{B}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
\lang american
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a4_{B}$
\end_inset

 respectively) and also nitrate with a inhibition factor due to ammonium.
 This flux regulates the direct uptake and the activity uptake based on
 the optimal quota and the net carbon uptake
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G_{B}=\sum_{j=1,2,6}\left.\frac{dB_{c}}{dt}\right|_{R_{c}^{(j)}}^{upt}-\left.\frac{dB_{c}}{dt}\right|_{O^{(3)}}^{rsp}.\label{eq:bacteria_net_growth}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Remineralization dynamics occur only when internal quotas are in excess
 with respect to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

optimal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 value and the dissolved nutrient uptake is linearly dependent on the membrane
 affinity as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\NSP\NSP\left.\frac{dB_{p}}{dt}\right|_{N^{(1)}}^{upt} & =\label{eq:bacteria_upt_P}\\
 & \NSP\NSP\NSP\NSP\min\left[a_{B}^{1}N^{(1)}B_{c},\max\left(0,\,p_{B}^{opt}G_{B}-\NSP\sum_{j=1,6}\left.\frac{dB_{p}}{dt}\right|_{R_{p}^{(j)}}^{upt}\right)\right]\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{dB_{p}}{dt}\right|_{N^{(1)}}^{rel}=\max\left(0,\,\sum_{j=1,6}\left.\frac{dB_{p}}{dt}\right|_{R_{p}^{(j)}}^{upt}-p_{_{P}}^{opt}G_{B}\right)\label{eq:bacteria_rel_P}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{dB_{n}}{dt}\right|_{N^{(4)}}^{rel}=\max\left(0,\,\sum_{j=1,6}\left.\frac{dB_{n}}{dt}\right|_{R_{n}^{(j)}}^{upt}-n_{B}^{opt}G_{B}\right)\label{eq:bacteria_rel_N}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\NSP\!\!\sum_{i=3,4}\!\!\!\!\left.\frac{dB_{n}}{dt}\right|_{N^{(i)}}^{upt} & \!\!\!\NSP=\!\!\min\!\!\,\left(a4_{B}\frac{h_{B}^{n}}{h_{B}^{n}+N^{(4)}}N^{(3)}+a4_{B}N^{(4)}\!\!\right)\!B_{n},\nonumber \\
 & \left.\max\left(0,\,n_{B}^{opt}G_{B}-\sum_{j=1,6}\left.\frac{dB_{n}}{dt}\right|_{R_{n}^{(j)}}^{upt}\right)\right)\label{eq:bacteria_upt_N}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
BACT3 parameterization 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:BACT3"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Substrate uptake
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The organic substrate uptake differs from the BACT1 and BACT2 parameterizations
 not only for the wider resolution of the DOM lability/refractivity characterist
ics given in the introduction, but also because the DOC uptake is not constraine
d by the nutritional content of bacterial cells (see eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bact_quota_regulation"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{j=1,2,3,6}\NSP\left.\frac{dB_{c}}{dt}\right|_{R_{c}^{(j)}}^{upt}=\min\left(f_{_{B}}^{T}f_{_{B}}^{o}r_{0_{B}}B_{c},\NSP\sum_{j=1,2,3,6}\nu_{B}^{R^{(j)}}R_{c}^{(j)}\right)\label{eq:bacteria_bcd}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The uptake of the nutrient components in the dissolved and particulate fractions
 is instead the same defined for BACT1 (eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:subnut_upt"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Nutrient release and uptake
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Nutrient release and uptake parameterization is the same described for
 the BACT1 version (see Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:BACT1-Nutrient-release-uptake"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Excretion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This version also defines a bacterial first-order excretion of carbohydrates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{dB_{c}}{dt}\right|_{R_{c}^{(2)}}^{rel}=\max\left(0,1-\frac{B_{p}/B_{c}}{p_{_{B}}^{^{opt}}},1-\frac{B_{n}/B_{c}}{n_{_{B}}^{^{opt}}}\right)\nu_{B}B_{c}\label{eq:BACT3_releaseR2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

based on the optimal nutrient content and the constant relaxation time scale
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{B}$
\end_inset

.
 The release of semi refractory DOC is assumed to be at constant rate (
\begin_inset Formula $d^{-1}$
\end_inset

 ), assumed to be proportional to the activity respiration rates:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{dB_{c}}{dt}\right|_{R_{c}^{(3)}}^{rel}=\beta_{B}\sum_{j=1,2,3,6}\left.\frac{dB_{c}}{dt}\right|_{R_{c}^{(j)}}^{upt}\label{eq:BACT3_excretionR3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{B}$
\end_inset

 is the constant fraction of renewal of capsular material, usually equivalent
 to about 1/4 of the respiration rate 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "stoderegger98"

\end_inset

.
 Note that this parameter must be set by the user and a warning is issued
 if the resulting bacterial growth efficiency is too low.
\end_layout

