\begin_layout Subsection
Food availability
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Zoo-Food-availability"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total amount of food available to zooplankton is computed considering
 the set of possible preys 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}\in\left\{ P_{i}^{(j)},B_{i},Z_{i}^{(j)}\right\} $
\end_inset

 as the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}=\sum_{X}\delta_{_{Z,X}}e_{_{Z,X}}X_{i}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{_{Z,X}}$
\end_inset

is the availability of prey 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 for predator Z and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{_{Z,X}}$
\end_inset

 is the capture efficiency.
 The product of the latter terms gives the total preference.
 There are many definitions of preferences in the literature, and we have
 used concepts from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "gentleman03"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "gibson05"

\end_inset

 to combine the parameterizations described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "barettabekker95"

\end_inset

 for microzooplankton and in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "broekhuizen95"

\end_inset

 for mesozooplankton.
 Availability represents the suitability of the prey and is assumed to be
 mostly dependent on the prey's nominal dimensions.
 Capture efficiency (or relative preference) is also a non-dimensional factor
 which is set to 1 for mesozooplankton and it is density-dependent in microzoopl
ankton, 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{_{Z,X}}=\frac{X_{c}}{X_{c}+\mu_{Z}}$
\end_inset

, according to the threshold half-saturation density 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{Z}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{Z}=0$
\end_inset

 for mesozooplankton).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ingestion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first term on the right hand side of eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:zooplankton_C"

\end_inset

) is the total carbon ingestion, which corresponds to the sum of all the
 predation loss terms in the carbon equations of the other functional groups
 preyed by zooplankton.
 Applying the inter-functional group conversion defined in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:flip_flop_rule"

\end_inset

), the rate term for each predation processes is parameterized with a Type
 2 formulation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gentleman03"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{dZ_{c}}{dt}\right|_{X_{c}}^{prd}=-\left.\frac{dX_{c}}{dt}\right|_{Z_{c}}^{prd}=f_{_{Z}}^{T}\,r_{_{Z}}^{0}\frac{\delta_{_{Z,X}}e_{_{Z,X}}\,X_{c}}{F_{c}}\frac{F_{c}}{F_{c}+h_{Z}^{F}}Z_{c}\label{eq:zooplankton_predation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is traditionally rewritten in terms of the specific search volume
 in the case of mesozooplankton 
\begin_inset Formula $(h_{Z}^{F}=\frac{r_{0_{Z}}}{v_{_{Z}}})$
\end_inset

, because this parameter is generally available in the literature.
 For brevity, in the zooplankton equations we will use the following notation
 to indicate the total ingestion rate in units of each constituent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I_{j}=\sum_{X}\left.\frac{dZ_{j}}{dt}\right|_{X_{j}}^{prd}\,j=c,n,p.\label{eq:zooplankton_ingestion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Excretion/egestion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Metabolic rates in zooplankton are assumed to be closely coupled to growth,
 therefore total ingested carbon is used part for net production, part for
 respiration and the remainder is egested/excreted.
 The parameters that can be measured in laboratory experiments are net growth
 efficiency 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{_{Z}}$
\end_inset

  and the egested portion of ingested material 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{_{Z}}$
\end_inset

 .
 The ingestion rate in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:zooplankton_ingestion"

\end_inset

) is not directly affected by prey quality in our present formulation, although
 this process appears to modulate zooplankton feeding rates substantially
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "cf."
key "mitra05"

\end_inset

.
 Nevertheless, the definition of constant (optimal) nutrient quota in zooplankto
n 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barettabekker97"

\end_inset

, equivalent to the Threshold Elemental Ratios of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "TER"
key "andersen04"

\end_inset

, implies that the ingestion of low-quality (i.e.
 nutrient-poor) food lead to the disposal of the ingested carbon in excess,
 thus effectively limiting biomass growth.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, an excess of nutrients, as for instance due to the ingestion
 of phytoplankton under 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

luxury uptake
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 conditions, leads to an increase of the nutrient remineralization rates
 as shown below in eqs.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:zooplankton_out_P"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:zooplankton_out_N"

\end_inset

).
 The release of extra C is parameterized as an increase of the egestion
 rates of organic carbon compounds or,  alternatively, by increasing the
 respiration rates.
 Both processes are well documented in freshwater zooplankton 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "frost04,anderson05"

\end_inset

 and we have decided to parameterize  increased  excretion rates.
 The two pathways are equivalent from the point of view of internal element
 regulation in zooplankton, but the consequences of one choice or another
 on the biogeochemical cycling of carbon are still to be investigated both
 experimentally and in model studies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The carbon loss term in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:zooplankton_C"

\end_inset

) thus represents the sum of the activity excretion/egestion (higher for
 mesozooplankton because of sloppy feeding), the mortality rates and the
 nutrient-limited excretion of organic carbon.
 For the microzooplankton the carbon loos term reads: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{j=1,6}\left.\frac{dZ_{c}}{dt}\right|_{R_{c}^{(j)}}^{rel}=\beta_{_{Z}}I_{c}+(d_{0_{Z}}+d_{_{Z}}^{o}(1-f_{Z}^{o}))\,f_{_{Z}}^{T}\,Z_{c}\label{eq:zooplankton_out}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for mesozooplankton the carbon loss term reads:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{dZ_{c}}{dt}\right|_{R_{c}^{(6)}}^{rel}=\beta_{_{Z}}I_{c}+(d_{0_{Z}}+doxy_{0_{Z}}(1-f_{Z}^{o}))\,f_{_{Z}}^{T}\,Z_{c}+d_{_{Z}}^{dns}\,Z_{c}^{\gamma_{_{Z}}}+Q_{Z}^{c}\label{eq:zooplankton_out-3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The released fraction is further divided into particulate (faecal pellets)
 and dissolved organic forms using a constant percentage 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{_{Z}}^{c}$
\end_inset

 (mesozooplankton is assumed to have no dissolved products).
 Mortality is parameterized as senescence with a first-order rate based
 on a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{0_{Z}}$
\end_inset

, as oxygen regulated component 
\begin_inset Formula $doxy_{0_{Z}}$
\end_inset

, and as a grazing closure by higher trophic levels not resolved in the
 model, which is a power function of density valid only for mesozooplankton
 (
\begin_inset Formula $d_{_{Z}}^{dns}=0$
\end_inset

 for microzooplankton).
 
\end_layout

