\begin_layout Subsection
Oxygen and anoxic processes
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Oxygen-anoxic-processes"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dynamics of dissolved oxygen and carbon dioxide are important closures
 of global biogeochemical cycles.
 We do not describe here the exchange of gases at the air sea interface
 which is assumed to be a purely physical process and has been thoroughly
 investigated elsewhere, especially for CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "olsen05"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Anaerobic processes and denitrification dynamics are a consequence of oxygen
 dynamics and are described here for completeness, although they are of
 limited impact in the well-oxygenated euphotic zones of the open ocean.
 Nevertheless, these processes are important for the sulfur cycle and for
 the fate of exported carbon in the meso- and bathypelagic layers of the
 ocean, where bacteria are the major drivers of these processes.
 To account for hypoxic and anoxic remineralization in the water, the original
 ERSEM parameterization of anaerobic processes in the sediments proposed
 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ruardij95a"

\end_inset

 was extended to the pelagic system by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "vichi04"

\end_inset

.
 The state variable 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reduction equivalents
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{(6)}$
\end_inset

 (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:model_variables"

\end_inset

 and Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Scheme-Pelagic"

\end_inset

) is an inorganic state variable containing all the reduced chemical species
 and assumed to be chemically equivalent to the sulphide ion HS
\begin_inset Formula $^{-}$
\end_inset

.
 The basic constituent is indicated with the letter R because this variable
 account for all the reduced biochemical products, although it should be
 mostly regarded as sulphur S.
 Reduction equivalents are produced as a result of bacterial anoxic respiration
 and are partly used for the parameterization of denitrification processes
 and partly for direct sulphide production.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pelagic net production of oxygen is derived from the sum of gross primary
 production and community respiration rates from phytoplankton, zooplankton
 and bacteria, also subtracting the losses due to pelagic chemical reactions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left.\frac{dO^{(2)}}{dt}\right|_{bio} & = & \Omega_{_{c}}^{o}\sum_{j=1}^{3}\left(\left.\frac{dP_{c}^{(j)}}{dt}\right|_{O^{(3)}}^{gpp}-\left.\frac{dP_{c}^{(j)}}{dt}\right|_{O^{(3)}}^{rsp}\right)+\nonumber \\
 &  & -\Omega_{_{c}}^{o}\,f_{_{B}}^{o}\left.\frac{dB_{c}}{dt}\right|_{O^{(3)}}^{rsp}+\nonumber \\
 &  & -\Omega_{_{c}}^{o}\sum_{j=4}^{6}\left.\frac{dZ_{c}^{(j)}}{dt}\right|_{O^{(3)}}^{rsp}+\nonumber \\
 &  & -\Omega_{_{n}}^{o}\left.\frac{dN^{(4)}}{dt}\right|_{N^{(3)}}^{nit}\NSP-\frac{1}{\Omega_{_{o}}^{r}}\left.\frac{dN^{(6)}}{dt}\right|_{sink_{r}}^{reox}\label{eq:oxygen_O2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

All the rates are converted into oxygen units by means of constant stoichiometri
c coefficients.
  Since bacteria are active both under aerobic and anaerobic conditions
 the bacterial oxygen demand (eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bacteria_rsp"

\end_inset

) is partitioned into oxygen consumption and reduction equivalent production
 by using the oxygen regulating factor 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{_{B}}^{o}$
\end_inset

 in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bacteria_regfac_O"

\end_inset

).
 The nitrification rate is a source term of the nitrate equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:nitrate_N3n"

\end_inset

), and a sink term for ammonium (eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ammonium_N4n"

\end_inset

) and oxygen (eq.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:oxygen_O2"

\end_inset

).
 Nitrification is not explicitly resolved but parameterized with a simple
 first-order dependence on ammonium and oxygen concentrations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{dN^{(4)}}{dt}\right|_{N^{(3)}}^{nit}=\Lambda_{_{N^{(4)}}}^{nit}\,f_{_{n}}^{T}\,\frac{O^{(2)}}{O^{(2)}+h_{_{o}}}\,N^{(4)}\label{eq:nitrogen_nitrification}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{_{N4}}^{nit}$
\end_inset

 is the constant specific nitrification rate and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}^{T}$
\end_inset

 a temperature regulating factor with the Q10 formulation shown in (eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Q10"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formation of reduction equivalents is parameterized converting the biologica
l oxygen demand of bacteria (under low oxygen conditions) into sulphide
 ions by using the stoichiometric coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{_{o}}^{r}$
\end_inset

 as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left.\frac{dN^{(6)}}{dt}\right|_{bio}= & \Omega_{_{o}}^{r}\Omega_{_{c}}^{o}\left(1-f_{_{B1}}^{o}\right)\left.\frac{dB_{c}}{dt}\right|_{O^{(3)}}^{rsp}+\nonumber \\
 & -\Omega_{_{o}}^{r}\,\widetilde{\Omega}_{_{n}}^{o}\left.\frac{dN^{(3)}}{dt}\right|_{sink_{n}}^{denit}-\left.\frac{dN^{(6)}}{dt}\right|_{sink_{r}}^{reox}\label{eq:reduction_equivalents}
\end{align}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The utilization of nitrate as an electron acceptor in microbial metabolic
 reactions is parameterized in an indirect way.
 Firstly, when the oxygen level falls below the threshold level and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{_{B}}^{o}<1$
\end_inset

 (eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bacteria_regfac_O"

\end_inset

), the metabolic formation of reduction equivalents begins according to
 the carbon mineralization rate (eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bacteria_rsp"

\end_inset

).
 The denitrification reaction is favored with respect to the strictly anaerobic
 sulphate reduction, therefore a portion of this oxygen demand is redirected
 towards the denitrification process.
 In order to achieve this net effect, the changes in the redox conditions
 enhance the denitrification flux in the following way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\!\!\!\!\NSP\left.\frac{dN^{(3)}}{dt}\right|^{denit}\NSP= & \Lambda_{_{N^{(3)}}}^{denit}\,f_{_{n}}^{T}\left[\frac{1}{\mathcal{M}_{o}^{*}}\Omega_{_{c}}^{o}\left(1-f_{_{B}}^{o}\right)\left.\frac{dB_{c}}{dt}\right|_{O^{(3)}}^{rsp}\right]N^{(3)}\cdot\label{eq:nitrate_denitrification}
