\begin_layout Subsection
The carbonate system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The aquatic chemistry of inorganic carbon forms (state variable 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{(3)}$
\end_inset

) is a further extension to the original ERSEM formulation and it is activated
 with the key 
\family typewriter
INCLUDE_PELCO2
\family default
.
 The theory of dissolved inorganic carbon chemical reactions is well understood
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "zeebe01book"

\end_inset

 and we propose here a slightly revised formulation with respect to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "blackford02"

\end_inset

, which also takes into account the algorithms proposed by the Ocean Carbon
 Model Intercomparison Project 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doney04"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the ocean, inorganic carbon is present in three different forms: free
 carbon dioxide 
\begin_inset Formula $([CO_{2}]=[CO_{2}]_{aq}+[H_{2}CO_{3}]),$
\end_inset

 bicarbonate ion 
\begin_inset Formula $(HCO_{3}^{-})$
\end_inset

 and carbonate ion 
\begin_inset Formula $(CO_{3}^{2-})$
\end_inset

.
 These carbonate species reach the following equilibrium:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
CO_{2}+H_{2}O\rightleftharpoons HCO_{3}^{-}+H^{+}\rightleftharpoons CO_{3}^{2-}+2H^{+}\label{eq:K1K2equilibria}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

defined by the equilibrium constants 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{2}$
\end_inset

 for the first and second reaction, respectively.
 The carbonate system in seawater is described in terms of 7 chemical species,
 i.e., free carbon dioxide 
\begin_inset Formula $(CO_{2})$
\end_inset

, bicarbonate ion 
\begin_inset Formula $(HCO_{3}^{-})$
\end_inset

, carbonate ion 
\begin_inset Formula $(CO_{3}^{2-})$
\end_inset

, carbon dioxide partial pressure in seawater 
\begin_inset Formula $(pCO_{2})$
\end_inset

, hydrogen ion concentration 
\begin_inset Formula $(pH=-log_{10}([H^{+}]))$
\end_inset

, dissolved inorganic carbon concentration (
\begin_inset Formula $DIC$
\end_inset

) and total alkalinity (
\begin_inset Formula $TA$
\end_inset

).
 These species are governed by the following relations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K_{1}=\frac{[HCO_{3}^{-}]\cdot[H^{+}]}{[CO_{2}]}\label{eq:K1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K_{2}=\frac{[CO_{3}^{2-}]\cdot[H^{+}]}{[HCO_{3}^{-}]}\label{eq:K2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
DIC=[CO_{2}]+[HCO_{3}^{-}]+[CO_{3}^{2-}]\label{eq:DIC}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
pCO_{2}=\frac{[CO_{2}]}{K_{0}}\label{eq:pco2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
TA & = & [HCO_{3}^{-}]+2[CO_{3}^{2-}]+[B(OH)_{4}^{-}]+\nonumber \\
 &  & +[OH^{-}]+[HPO_{4}^{2-}]+2[PO_{4}^{3-}]+\label{eq:TA}\\
 &  & +[H_{3}SiO_{4}^{-}]-[H^{+}]_{F}-[HSO_{4}^{-}]+\nonumber \\
 &  & -[HF]-[H_{3}PO_{4}]
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The species appearing in this latter equation are expressed in terms of
 their equilibrium constants and their total elemental concentrations.
 Total alkalinity is therefore computed as a function of: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
TA & =f\,([H^{+}],\,DIC,\,K_{1},\,K_{2},\,K_{w},\,K_{b},\nonumber \\
 & \,K_{1p},\,K_{2p},\,K_{3p},\,K_{si},\,K_{s},\,K_{f},\,bt,\,st,\,ft,\label{eq:Ta_function}\\
 & \,O^{(3)},\,O^{(5)},\,N^{(5)},\,N^{(1)})
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{2}$
\end_inset

 are the previously seen equilibrium constants for carbonic acid 
\begin_inset Formula $(H_{2}CO_{3})$
\end_inset

 and bicarbonate ion 
\begin_inset Formula $(HCO_{3}^{-})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the Henry's constant which regulates 
\begin_inset Formula $CO_{2}$
\end_inset

 solubility in seawater, 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{w}$
\end_inset

 is the ion product of water, 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{b}$
\end_inset

 is the dissociation constant for boric acid 
\begin_inset Formula $(B(OH)_{3})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1p}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{2p}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{3p}$
\end_inset

 are the dissociation constants for phosphoric acid 
\begin_inset Formula $(H_{3}PO_{4})$
\end_inset

, di-hydrogen phosphate ion 
\begin_inset Formula $(H_{2}PO_{4}^{-})$
\end_inset

 and hydrogen phosphate ion 
\begin_inset Formula $(HPO_{4}^{2-})$
\end_inset

 respectively, 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{si}$
\end_inset

 is the dissociation constant for silicic acid 
\begin_inset Formula $(Si(OH)_{4})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the dissociation constant for bisulfate ion 
\begin_inset Formula $(HSO_{4}^{-})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{f}$
\end_inset

 is the dissociation constant for hydrogen fluoride 
\begin_inset Formula $(HF)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $bt$
\end_inset

 is the total boron concentration 
\begin_inset Formula $([B(OH)_{3}+[B(OH)_{4}^{-}])$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $st$
\end_inset

 is the total sulfate concentration 
\begin_inset Formula $([HSO_{4}^{-}]+[SO_{4}^{2-}])$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $ft$
\end_inset

 is the total fluoride concentration 
\begin_inset Formula $([HF]+[F^{-}])$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{(3)}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{(5)}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{(1)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N{}^{(5)}$
\end_inset

 are the model state variables for DIC, total alkalinity, total phosphorus
 concentration 
\begin_inset Formula $([H_{3}PO_{4}]+[H_{2}PO_{4}^{-}]+[HPO_{4}^{2-}]+[PO_{4}^{3-}])$
\end_inset

, and total silica concentration 
\begin_inset Formula $([Si(OH)_{4}]+[H_{3}SiO_{4}^{-}])$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 Note that total fluoride, sulfate and boron concentrations 
\begin_inset Formula $(ft$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $st$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $bt)$
\end_inset

 are given as dependent on the temperature and salinity only.
 Currently, the model does not take into account changes of alkalinity due
 to calcification.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The effects of biogeochemical processes on alkalinity linked to the N cycle
 are taken into account with a correction to the total alkalinity value
 after 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "wolf-gladrow07"

\end_inset

.
 The uptake of 1 mole of N leads to (i) an increase of alkalinity by 1 mole
 when nitrate is the source, (ii) to a decrease of alkalinity by 1 mole
 when ammonia is used.
 Nitrification leads to a decrease of TA by 2 moles per mole of nitrate
 formed and denitrification leads to an increase of TA by 1 mole per mole
 of nitrate converted.
 Thus, considering the equations in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:nitrate_N3n"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ammonium_N4n"

\end_inset

), the source form equation for TA reads: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left.\frac{dO^{(5)}}{dt}\right|_{bio} & = & \sum_{j=1}^{4}\left.\frac{dP_{n}^{(j)}}{dt}\right|_{N^{(3)}}^{upt}-\sum_{j=1}^{4}\left.\frac{dP_{n}^{(j)}}{dt}\right|_{N^{(4)}}^{upt}+\nonumber \\
 &  & -2\left.\frac{dN^{(3)}}{dt}\right|_{N^{(4)}}^{nit}+\left.\frac{dN^{(3)}}{dt}\right|_{sink_{n}}^{denit}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equilibrium constants are also computed from temperature and salinity
 according to the methods described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "zeebe01book"

\end_inset

 where the total 
\begin_inset Formula $pH$
\end_inset

 scale is used.
 The carbonate equilibrium calculation is done in units of 
\begin_inset Formula $mol\cdot kg^{-1}$
\end_inset

, therefore conversions from model units are done by taking into account
 the actual seawater density.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a five equation system (eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:K1"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TA"

\end_inset

) with seven unknown variables: the system is therefore determined when
 two of the seven variables are known, which in this case are DIC and TA.
 Total alkalinity equation is used to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $[H^{+}]$
\end_inset

 by means of the Newton-Raphson convergence method.
 A dedicated diagnostic variable is also introduced to store the total hydrogen
 ions and to allow the restart of the model from previous simulations.
 The other carbon species are eventually computed from the carbonate equilibrium
 equations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively, the model allows the usage of a simplified computation of
 DIC equilibria as suggested by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "follows06"

\end_inset

, which does not imply an iterative procedure.
 This solution is suggested for coupled configurations because in that case
 the inaccuracy of the computation is less important due to the presence
 of advective and diffusive processes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, the biological production and consumption of CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 considered in the model can be easily derived by collecting the first 4
 terms on the right hand side of eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:oxygen_O2"

\end_inset

) without considering the stoichiometric factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{_{c}}^{o}$
\end_inset

 and taking the total bacterial respiration as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left.\frac{dO^{(3)}}{dt}\right|_{bio}= & \sum_{j=1}^{3}\left(\left.\frac{dP_{c}^{(j)}}{dt}\right|_{O^{(3)}}^{gpp}-\left.\frac{dP_{c}^{(j)}}{dt}\right|_{O^{(3)}}^{rsp}\right)+\nonumber \\
 & -\left.\frac{dB_{c}}{dt}\right|_{O^{(3)}}^{rsp}-\sum_{k=4,5,6}\left.\frac{dZ_{c}^{(k)}}{dt}\right|_{O^{(3)}}^{rsp}\label{eq:carbon_dioxide}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parameters of the carbonate system are controlled with a specific namelist
 found in file Carbonate_Dynamics.nml and listed in Tab.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Parameters-carbonate"

\end_inset

.
 The namelist also allows to read an external file containing data for atmospher
