\begin_layout Standard
Each state variable interacts with the others through the universal physiologica
l and ecological processes depicted in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BFM-SI"

\end_inset

.
 This component already includes parameterizations of sea ice bacteria and
 fauna, which follow the same dynamics as their counterpart in the pelagic
 realm.
 Nonetheless, both groups are technically available for future studies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As for the pelagic model, nitrate is assumed here to be the sum of both
 nitrite and nitrate.
 All the nutrient:carbon ratios in chemical organic and living functional
 groups are allowed to vary within their given range and each component
 has a distinct biological time rate of change.
 This kind of parametrization is meant to mimic the adaptation of organisms
 to the diverse availability of nutrients and light observed in nature,
 and also allow to recycle organic matter depending on the actual nutrient
 content.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Sea ice Algae Dynamics
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:algae"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a first implementation of the BFM in sea ice, 2 distinct subgroups have
 been chosen as representative of sea ice primary producers: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Adapted diatoms, which are meant to be highly adapted to the environment
 and also show distinct skills in acclimation.
 They are supposed to be first light-limited and, later in the bloom, dependent
 on nutrient availability.
 They have an Equivalent Spherical Diameter (ESD) of 20-200 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

m and preyed by adult mesozooplankton (> 200 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

m) and microzooplankton of larger dimensions (20-200 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

m), which are not currently present in the sea ice system, but act in the
 pelagic BFM when sea ice melts and algae are released in the water column.
 Sea ice diatoms are the main source of biogenic silica and differ from
 the other subgroup being their growth limited by dissolved silicate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Surviving sea ice algae, which may be mostly represented by autotrophic
 nanoflagellates, are meant to only survive in the sea ice environment,
 being less adapted to it and showing lower skills of acclimation.
 However, they may be able to grow in sea ice if the diatoms bloom is quickly
 exhausted - for instance, for depletion of silicate - and a sufficient
 amount of nutrients is still available for their growth.
 Their ESD is 2-20 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

m and are mainly externally preyed by pelagic microzooplankton.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mathematical notation used here is the same defined for the pelagic
 BFM (Chap 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:BFM-formalism"

\end_inset

).
 Sea ice algae are involved in several processes: gross primary production
 (gpp), respiration (rsp), exudation (exu), cell lysis (lys), nutrient uptake
 (upt), predation (prd) and biochemical synthesis (syn).
 Both subgroups share the same form of primitive equations, but are differentiat
ed in terms of the values of the physiological parameters (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:BFM-SI_parameters"

\end_inset

).
 There are 5 living CFFs that describe the constituents of the generic variable
 sea ice algae 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (with constituents C, N, P, Si and Chl, see Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:BFM-SI_variables"

\end_inset

) and thus for each group we have 4 or 5 equations as shown in Equation
 Box 
