\begin_layout Standard
The rate of change of carbon in sea ice algae depends on gross primary productio
n, exudation, respiration, lysis and predation (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:algae_c"

\end_inset

).
 Gross primary production is the rate of change of sea ice algae carbon
 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{c}$
\end_inset

 due to photosynthesis, which involves an uptake of dissolved carbon dioxide
 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{(3)}.$
\end_inset

 It is written as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{dA_{c}}{dt}\Biggr|_{F^{(3)}}^{gpp}=f_{A}^{T}\,f_{A}^{E}\,f_{A}^{s}\,r_{A}^{0}\,A_{c}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{A}^{0}$
\end_inset

 is the maximum specific photosynthetic rate under nutrient-replete, light
 saturated conditions (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:BFM-SI_parameters"

\end_inset

).
 The 
\shape italic
f
\shape default
 functions are multiplicative, non-dimensional regulating factors for temperatur
e, light and silicate, which vary from 0 to 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Temperature is regulating several physiological processes.
 Its effect is expressed in a non-dimensional form by 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{A}^{T}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
f_{A}^{T}=Q{_{10}^{A}}^{\frac{T-10}{10}}\label{eq:q10}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{10}^{A}$
\end_inset

 is the characteristic doubling temperature parameter (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:BFM-SI_parameters"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many relevant biological processes, such as potential photosynthesis, are
 also affected by the non-dimensional light regulating factor 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{A}^{E}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
f_{A}^{E}=1-exp\:\Biggl(-\frac{E_{PAR}}{E_{K}}\Biggr)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{PAR}$
\end_inset

 is the Photosynthetic Available Radiation (PAR).
 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{PAR}$
\end_inset

 is parametrized according to the Lambert-Beer formulation with depth-dependent
 extinction coefficients: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
E_{PAR}(z)=\varepsilon_{PAR}F_{sw}e^{(\lambda_{s}+\lambda_{i})z+\intop_{z}^{0}\lambda_{bio}(z')dz'}\label{eq:PAR}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{sw}$
\end_inset

 is the short-wave surface irradiance flux and may be derived from data
 or from a coupled physical model, such as the one of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "tedesco09a,tedesco10"

\end_inset

.
 The irradiance flux is then converted by BFM-SI from W m
\begin_inset Formula $^{-2}$
\end_inset

 to the units of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

E m
\begin_inset Formula $^{-2}$
\end_inset

 s
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 as done in the pelagic model.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{PAR}$
\end_inset

 is the coefficient determining the portion of PAR in 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{sw}$
\end_inset

.
 Light propagation takes into account the extinction due to the background
 extinction of snow/sea ice 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{s,i}$
\end_inset

 and due to particles in the sea ice 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{bio}$
\end_inset

, where: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\lambda_{bio}=\sum_{j}^{2}c_{A}A_{l}^{(j)}+c_{U^{(6)}}U_{c}^{(6)}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{bio}$
\end_inset

 takes into consideration the extinction due to sea ice algae chlorophyll
 and to particulate detritus, while dissolved substances and other inorganic
 matter are not currently taken into account.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{U}$
\end_inset

 constants are the specific absorption coefficients of each suspended substance
 (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:BFM-SI_parameters"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $E_{K}$
\end_inset

 is the light saturation parameter, that is the ratio between the maximum
 chl-
\shape slanted
a
\shape default
 specific photosynthetic rate and the maximum light utilization coefficient,
 i.e.: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
E_{K}=\frac{P_{m}^{*}}{\alpha^{*}}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

As for pelagic phytoplankton of BFM: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{m}^{*}=f_{A}^{T}f_{A}^{s}r_{A}^{0}\frac{A_{c}}{A_{l}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\alpha^{*}=f_{A}^{T}f_{A}^{s}\alpha_{chl}^{0}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{A}^{T}$
\end_inset

 is the regulating factor for temperature, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{A}^{s}$
\end_inset

 is the regulating factor for silicate, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{A}^{0}$
\end_inset

 is the maximum specific photosynthetic rate under nutrient-replete, light-satur
ated conditions and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{chl}^{0}$
\end_inset

 is the maximum slope of the production-irradiance curve at optimal conditions
 (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:BFM-SI_parameters"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{A}^{s}\,$
\end_inset

 is parametrized as an external limiting factor with a Michaelis-Menten
 form: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
f_{A}^{s}=\frac{I^{(5)}}{I^{(5)}+d_{s}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the Michaelis-Menten constant for SiO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 uptake inhibition (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:BFM-SI_parameters"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exudation rate of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:algae_c"

\end_inset

) reads: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{dA_{c}}{dt}\Biggr|_{U_{c}^{(1)}}^{exu}=[\beta_{A}+\nonumber \\
(1-\beta_{A})(1-f_{A}^{n,p})]\frac{dA_{c}}{dt}\Biggr|_{F^{(3)}}^{gpp}\label{eq:exuC}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{A}$
\end_inset

 is a constant fraction of carbon uptake (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:BFM-SI_parameters"

\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{A}^{n,p}$
\end_inset

 is a Liebig-like regulating factor for internal nutrient ratio: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
f_{A}^{n,p}=min\Biggr(\frac{A_{n}/A_{c}-n_{A}^{min}}{n_{A}^{opt}-n_{A}^{min}},\nonumber \\
\frac{A_{p}/A_{c}-p_{A}^{min}}{p_{A}^{opt}-p_{A}^{min}}\Biggr)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n(p)_{A}^{opt}$
\end_inset

 is the nitrate(phosphate) optimal ratio, while 
\begin_inset Formula $n(p)_{A}^{min}$
\end_inset

 is the nitrate(phosphate) minimum quota (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:BFM-SI_parameters"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The respiration rate of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:algae_c"

\end_inset

) is written as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{dA_{c}}{dt}\Biggr|_{F^{(3)}}^{rsp}=f_{A}^{T}b_{A}A_{c}+\nonumber \\
\gamma_{A}\Biggr(\frac{dA_{c}}{dt}\Biggr|_{F^{(3)}}^{gpp}-\frac{dA_{c}}{dt}\Biggr|_{U_{c}^{(1)}}^{exu}\Biggr)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{A}^{T}$
\end_inset

 is the metabolic regulating factor for temperature, 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{A}$
\end_inset

 is a constant specific rate of respiration and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{A}$
\end_inset

 is a fraction of the assimilated production (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:BFM-SI_parameters"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The loss of carbon via lysis of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:algae_c"

\end_inset

) is written as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\sum_{j=1,6}\frac{dA_{c}}{dt}\Biggr|_{U_{c}^{(j)}}^{lys}=\frac{1}{f_{A}^{p,n}+d_{A}^{p,n}}d_{O_{A}}A_{c}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{A}^{p,n}$
\end_inset

 is the nutrient stress threshold and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{O_{A}}$
\end_inset

 is the maximum specific lysis rate (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:BFM-SI_parameters"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The chlorophyll rate of change of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:algae_chl"

\end_inset

) is due to chlorophyll synthesis.
 The net chlorophyll synthesis is a function of acclimation to light conditions,
 nutrient availability and turnover rate.
 As in BFM, it is assumed that nutrient-stressed cells releasing substantial
 amounts of dissolved organic carbon tend to regulate their internal chl:C
 ratio in order to avoid unconstrained decreases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rate of change of net photosynthesis is thus primarily controlled by
 the dynamical chl:C ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{chl}$
\end_inset

 proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "geider98"

\end_inset

, which regulates the amount of chl-
\shape slanted
a
\shape default
 in the cell according to a non-dimensional ratio between the realized photosynt
hetic rate in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:algae_chl"

\end_inset

) and the maximum potential photosynthesis, i.e.: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\theta_{chl}=\theta_{chl}^{0}\frac{f_{A}^{E}r_{A}^{0}A_{c}}{\alpha_{chl}^{0}E_{PAR}A_{l}}\label{eq:photosynthesis}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{chl}^{0}$
\end_inset

 is the maximum quotum chl-
\shape slanted
a
\shape default
:C and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{chl}^{0}$
\end_inset

is the maximum slope of the production-irradiance curve at optimal growth
 conditions (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:BFM-SI_parameters"

\end_inset

).
 The same considerations about down-regulation and chlorophyll losses as
 detailed in Sec.
  
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Chlorophyll-synthesis-acclimation"

\end_inset

 for phytoplankton are valid for sea ice algae.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Nutrient Supply and Dynamics
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:seaice_nutrients"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nutrients supply for algal growth comes from the mixed layer up to the ice
 sheet for sustaining bottom communities, but also from snow deposition
 through brine drainage for surface communities and from 
\shape slanted
in situ
\shape default
 regeneration processes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even in isolated brine pockets, bacteria, heterotrophic protozoa and small
 metazoans have been shown to regenerate the major nutrients 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "arri95"

\end_inset

, but not silicate.
 Silicate dissolution and regeneration may be slower than demand and can
 be the major limiting factor for diatoms growth 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "lizo91"

\end_inset

, shifting the community from being diatom-dominated to flagellates-dominated
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "diec91"

\end_inset

.
 The slow regeneration of silicate in sea ice is parametrized in BFM-SI
 as a smaller value for the half saturation of silica and a larger value
 for the standard Si:C quotum in adapted diatoms (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:BFM-SI_parameters"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The boundary fluxes are currently added as additional source terms to the
 biogeochemical equations and solved explicitly.
 For instance, in the case of an inorganic nutrient in sea ice (e.g.
 nitrate, 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{(3)}$
\end_inset

), the complete equation is written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{dI^{(3)}}{dt}=\frac{dA_{n}^{(1)}}{dt}\Biggr|_{I^{(3)}}^{upt}+\frac{dA_{n}^{(2)}}{dt}\Biggr|_{I^{(3)}}^{upt}+\frac{dI^{(3)}}{dt}\Biggr|_{N^{(3)}}^{flux}\label{eq:tot_nut}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the first two terms on the right hand side represent the uptake from
 sea ice algae and the last one is the flux of nutrient at the boundaries.
 The external mechanisms of nutrients replenishment (exchange with the ocean
 and atmospheric deposition) will be analyzed in the next sections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The uptake of nitrogen and phosphorous by algae (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:tot_nut"

\end_inset

) is regulated by a Droop kinetics: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\sum_{i=3,4}\frac{dA_{n}}{dt}\Biggr|_{I^{(i)}}^{upt}=min\Biggr(\Big(a_{A}^{3}I^{(3)}\nonumber \\
+a_{A}^{4}I^{(4)}\Big)A_{c},n_{A}^{opt}G_{A}\nonumber \\
+f_{A}^{T}r_{A}^{0}\Big(n_{A}^{max}-\frac{A_{n}}{A_{c}}\Big)A_{c}\Biggr)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{dA_{p}}{dt}\Biggr|_{I^{(1)}}^{upt}=min\Biggr(a_{A}^{1}I^{(1)}A_{c},p_{A}^{opt}G_{A}\nonumber \\
+f_{A}^{T}r_{A}^{0}\Big(p_{A}^{max}-\frac{A_{p}}{A_{c}}\Big)A_{c}\Biggr)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 constants are the membrane affinity for nitrate, ammonium and phosphate
 (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:BFM-SI_parameters"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The uptake of silicate is, instead, only function of the maximum Si:C ratio
 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{A^{(1)}}^{max}$
\end_inset

 and of the net production 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{A^{(1)}}$
\end_inset

 of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:algae_c"

\end_inset

): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{dA_{s}}{dt}\Biggr|_{I^{(5)}}^{upt}=s_{A^{(1)}}^{max}G_{A^{(1)}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whenever sea ice algae carbon is lost by lysis, a proportional loss is found
 for algae nutrient content and is distributed between a dissolved and a
 particulate fraction.
 For instance, the equations of the lysis rate for phosphorous are: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{dA_{p}}{dt}\Biggr|_{U_{p}^{(6)}}^{lys}=p_{A}^{min}\frac{\partial A_{c}}{\partial t}\Biggr|_{U_{c}^{(6)}}^{lys}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{dA_{p}}{dt}\Biggr|_{U_{p}^{(1)}}^{lys}=\frac{A_{p}}{A_{c}}\sum_{j=1,6}\frac{\partial A_{c}}{\partial t}\Biggr|_{U_{c}^{(j)}}^{lys}-\frac{\partial A_{p}}{\partial t}\Biggr|_{U_{p}^{(6)}}^{lys}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Silicate is instead only released in particulate form: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\partial A_{s}^{(1)}}{dt}\Biggr|_{U_{s}^{(6)}}^{lys}=\frac{A_{s}^{(1)}}{A_{c}^{(1)}}\frac{\partial A_{c}^{(1)}}{\partial t}\Biggr|_{U_{c}^{(6)}}^{lys}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Gases and Detritus 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following equations are derived by combining terms from the previous
 sections in order to ensure mass conservation.
 The net production of oxygen is due to the gross primary production and
 to algae respiration rates:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial F^{(2)}}{\partial t}\Biggr|_{bio}=\Omega_{c}^{o}\sum_{j=1}^{2}\Biggr(\frac{\partial A_{c}^{(j)}}{\partial t}\Biggr|_{F^{(3)}}^{gpp}-\frac{\partial A_{c}^{j}}{\partial t}\Biggr|_{F^{(3)}}^{rsp}\Biggr)
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{c}^{o}$
\end_inset

 is the stoichiometric conversion factor to oxygen units in respiration
 and photosynthesis (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:BFM-SI_parameters"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dissolved organic matter (DOM, 
\shape italic

\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}^{(1)}$
\end_inset


\shape default
 in BFM-SI) is a non-living functional group including C, N and P constituents.
 In this current implementation, DOM is produced by sea ice algae (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:exuC"

\end_inset

), though in the complete setup shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BFM-SI"

\end_inset

 , DOM will be produced also by sea ice bacteria and microzooplankton: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\partial U_{c}^{(1)}}{\partial t}\Biggr|_{bio}=\sum_{j=1}^{2}\frac{\partial A_{c}^{(j)}}{\partial t}\Biggr|_{U_{c}^{(1)}}^{exu}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\partial U_{i}^{(1)}}{\partial t}\Biggr|_{bio}=\sum_{j=1}^{2}\frac{\partial A_{i}^{(j)}}{\partial t}\Biggr|_{U_{i}^{(1)}}^{exu}i=n,p.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Particulate organic matter (POM, 
\shape italic

\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}^{(6)}$
\end_inset


\shape default
 in BFM-SI) is made of C, N, P and Si: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\partial U_{c}^{(6)}}{\partial t}\Biggr|_{bio}=\sum_{j=1}^{2}\frac{\partial A_{c}^{(j)}}{\partial t}\Biggr|_{U_{c}^{(6)}}^{lys}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\partial U_{i}^{(6)}}{\partial t}\Biggr|_{bio}=\sum_{j=1}^{2}\frac{\partial A_{i}^{(j)}}{\partial t}\Biggr|_{U_{i}^{(6)}}^{lys}i=n,p,s
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the silicate component of POM is only valid for the release of sea
 ice diatoms frustules.
\end_layout

