\begin_layout Subsection
Boundary fluxes: the sea ice-ocean interface
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:ice-ocean"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The major exchanges between the sea ice and the pelagic systems are the
 fluxes of organic and inorganic matter at the interface.
 Ice structure determines the porosity and therefore the rate of exchange:
 frazil ice is less porous than congelation ice and algae may experience,
 for instance, nutrient depletion in the former.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rates of advection and diffusion of dissolved and particulate substances
 from seawater into the porous bottom layer of ice may also depend on under-ice
 current velocities, tides and atmospheric pressure cycles 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "cota91a"

\end_inset

.
 Additionally, high algal biomass in the platelet layer has been found to
 reduce the flux of nutrients to algae communities of the upper congelation
 layer in Antarctica 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "lizo91"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
High biomass is usually found in area of slow ice growth rate 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "lege92"

\end_inset

.
 During the growth season, convection in the skeletal layer enhances nutrient
 fluxes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "cota91a"

\end_inset

.
 During the melting season, the supply of freshwater increases the stratificatio
n just below the ice and reduces the flux of nutrients upward by reducing
 mixing and friction velocity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "goss85"

\end_inset

.
 Even if the enlargement and interconnections of the brine channels allows
 a greater biomass accumulation and nutrient supply, it also leads to an
 increase in the biological loss by cells sinking in the water column.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is assumed here that the entrapment of dissolved matter follows the same
 partitioning of salt in sea ice, that is the dynamics of dissolved constituents
 is treated as the salinity dynamics, as proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "tedesco09a"

\end_inset

, considering the concentration of dissolved matter in seawater and sea
 ice growth rate.
 Fluxes are defined positive upward, i.e.
 towards sea ice in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BAL_coupling"

\end_inset

.
 The nitrate flux is described here as an example of an inorganic nutrient
 exchange.
 The flux is composed of a positive part (entrapment) during sea ice formation
 when sea ice growth is positive, and of a negative part during the melting
 phase: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{dI^{(3)}}{dt}\Biggr|_{N^{(3)}}^{flux-oce}=\max\left(0,\frac{\partial h_{i}}{\partial t}\right)\cdot\nonumber \\
\max\left(0,\:N^{(3)}-\frac{I^{(3)}}{h_{bio}}\right)\nonumber \\
+\min\left(0,\frac{\partial h_{i}}{\partial t}\right)\frac{I^{(3)}}{h_{bio}}\ \label{eq:seaice_nutrient_flux}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{(3)}$
\end_inset

 is the nitrate concentration in seawater, 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the ice thickness and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{bio}$
\end_inset

 is the thickness of the biologically active layer in sea ice.
 When ice starts melting (the last term in the equation above), the release
 to the water column depends only on the sea ice melting rate and on the
 sea ice concentration.
 The same flux, converted into units of volume concentration, is included
 with opposite sign in the dynamical equation for pelagic nutrients.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The entrapment of particulate matter is assumed to be only a function of
 the seawater concentration, the sea ice growth rate and the actual available
 space in the sea ice matrix (brine volume, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{bio}$
\end_inset

), while the release during the melting phase is parametrized as function
 of the sea ice melting rate and sea ice concentrations, as in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:seaice_nutrient_flux"

\end_inset

).
 For instance, the flux of the chlorophyll component of sea ice algae 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{l}^{(1)}$
\end_inset

, from the pelagic variable 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{l}^{(1)}$
\end_inset

 to sea ice is defined as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{dA_{l}^{(1)}}{dt}\Biggr|_{P^{(1)}}^{flux-oce}=\max\left(0,\frac{\partial h_{i}}{\partial t}\right)P_{l}^{(1)}\,V_{bio}\nonumber \\
+\min\left(0,\frac{\partial h_{i}}{\partial t}\right)\frac{A_{l}^{(1)}}{h_{bio}}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Boundary fluxes: the sea ice-atmosphere interface
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:ice-atmosphere"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nutrient content in snow and liquid precipitation may directly lead to additiona
l nutrient availability for surface communities, and indirectly to internal
 and bottom communities, and finally to surface waters once sea ice has
 totally melted away.
 In the Baltic Sea, for instance, 5% of the total annual flux of N and P
 and 20--40% of lead and cadmium are deposited as snow: due to the intense
 stratification of most of the Baltic waters, sea ice is the major source
 of nutrients and trace elements to the surface Baltic waters during the
 melting season 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gran06a"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The physical processes responsible of the bioavailability of atmospheric
 nutrients to the sea ice community are snow ice formation and snow flushing.
 When snow ice forms the fraction of snow that mixes with flooding seawater
 may bring an additional source of nutrients for internal communities, while
 during snow flushing episodes the accumulated nutrients in the melting
 snow may become available also for bottom communities, if brines are permeable.
 This latter process is the one that it is currently considered in the model
 for the parametrization of the flux of atmospheric nutrients to bottom
 sea ice, as shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BAL_coupling"

\end_inset

.
 Phosphate and nitrogen concentration in snow may be derived from an atmospheric
 model or may be prescribed using available observations.
 The flux of nutrients due to precipitation becomes then a linear function
 of the snow melting rate, similarly to the flux of matter from sea ice
 to the ocean during melting of sea ice, i.e.
 for nitrate: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{dI^{(3)}}{dt}\Biggr|_{N^{snow}}^{flux-atm}=\min\left(0,\frac{\partial h_{s}}{\partial t}\right)N^{snow}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{snow}$
\end_inset

 is the nitrate concentration in snow and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the snow thickness.
 
\end_layout

