\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Forcing-functions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The STANDALONE model can be forced with different kind of forcing functions
 to provide the physical information for the aquatic system (e.g.
 temperature, irradiance, etc.).
 Two options are currently available: analytical forcing functions and data
 from an external file.
 All external data formats and time interpolations are derived from the
 code provided by GOTM under the GPL.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Analytical forcing functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This option is activated by setting 
\family typewriter
forcing_method=1
\family default
 in the namelist forcings_nml (Tab.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:parameters-time-manager"

\end_inset

).
 The simple analytical forcing functions give the user a easily accessible
 and quickly usable basic set-up of the physical forcing fields.
 The basic concept behind all forcing functions is the interpolation of
 some (northern hemisphere) summer and winter values by a sine wave, considering
 them as the two extreme values.
 This simple case is used for salinity forcing data (
\family typewriter
sw
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
ss
\family default
 in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Parameters-forcings"

\end_inset

), while for temperature, in addition to the sine wave, it is possible to
 superimpose a daily excursion (constant all over the year).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Light forcing is interpolated with a sine wave from a winter minimum value
 to a summer maximum value (
\family typewriter
lw
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
sw
\family default
 in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Parameters-forcings"

\end_inset

) to obtain the actual value of average daylight for each day of the year.
 These variables are as well intended as the placeholders for instantaneous
 light values and average daylight, i.
 e.
 the mean value of light energy over the light period: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{\mathit{daylength}}\int_{\tau_{\mathit{dawn}}}^{\tau_{\mathit{dusk}}}\mathit{light}(t)\mathit{dt}
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The daylength is computed by the model as a function of the latitude value
 given in the namelist .
 In case of the instantaneous light option (
\family typewriter
ltype=1
\family default
) the average daylight is distributed in a sine wave over the daylight period
 reaching thus a maximum of twice the average daylight while being zero
 at the beginning and in the end of the light period.
 In the case of constant light (
\family typewriter
ltype=2
\family default
) the mean daylight is smoothed out over the whole day by the factor 
\family typewriter
daylength/24
\family default
.
 In the case of rectangular light distribution (
\family typewriter
ltype=3
\family default
) the light equals the average daylight value over the whole daylight period
 and is zero at night time.
 In order to setup a constant-light experiment, it is sufficient to put
 the winter value equal to the summer value and set 
\family typewriter
ltype=2.
\end_layout

