\begin_layout Section
Coding rules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The BFM is written in plain F90 and it can generally be compiled with any
 F90 (and above) compiler.
 There are no fixed coding rules apart from standard clean programming.
 For historical reasons, the subroutine and symbols of the BFM biogeochemistry
 module are indicated with C-style capitalized long-names (e.g.
 EcologyDynamics), even if F90 does not distinguish capital letters.
 Constants and main memory arrays are generally indicated with capital names,
 to highlight their global static behavior.
 It is recommended to follow this style when possible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Memory layout and variable definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Memory-layout"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The BFM is structured similarly as the original ERSEM used to be.
 Pelagic variables are defined as virtually 3-dimensional, while benthic
 and sea ice variables are 2-dimensional.
 Only the sea-points are stored in memory, and thus the BFM has no knowledge
 of any land-sea mask or spatial relationships between grid-points in general.
 The number of bottom points is the same as the number of surface points,
 therefore the 2-D arrays can also be used for the surface variables and/or
 surface fluxes.
 These definitions are also maintained when the model is applied to a 1-D
 vertical setup.
 In that case, the pelagic variables have the spatial dimension of the number
 of vertical layers while the benthic and surface variables have dimension
 1 (the bottom and surface levels, with the index depending on the definitions
 of the physical model).
 In a 0-D setup (as in the STANDALONE test cases described in Chap.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Running-the-STANDALONE"

\end_inset

), the same grid-point is at the same time a bottom, surface and ocean layer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Layout-of-memory"

\end_inset

 illustrates the memory layout of pelagic variables.
 They are gathered in a single 2-dimensional array holding the number of
 different variables and the number of ocean grid-points: 
\begin_inset listings
lstparams "basicstyle={\normalsize\ttfamily}"
inline false
status open

\begin_layout LyX-Code

D3STATE(NO_D3_BOX_STATES,NO_BOXES)
\end_layout

\end_inset

and the same is done for the 2-dimensional variables (defined for the benthic
 and sea ice ecosystem models):
\begin_inset listings
lstparams "basicstyle={\normalsize\ttfamily}"
inline false
status open

\begin_layout LyX-Code

D2STATE(NO_D2_BOX_STATES,NO_BOXES_XY)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each variable memory is accessed by means of a pointer to the corresponding
 row containing all the grid-point values.
 This pointer array has the same naming convention of ERSEM.
 The rows are numbered with named constants starting with the letters 
\family typewriter
pp
\family default
 (
\family typewriter
ppP1c
\family default
 for phytoplankton carbon, 
\family typewriter
ppN1n
\family default
 for nitrate or 
\family typewriter
ppR1p
\family default
 for dissolved organic phosphorus, etc.).
 When the BFM is coupled to a 3-D model, then a mapping function must be
 taken into account as shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Layout-of-memory"

\end_inset

 in order to compute the transport terms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to this direct mechanism, the memory can be accessed by means
 of 
\emph on
group functions
\emph default
.
 These functions have been created to allow the addition of any number of
 sub-groups in the same trophic compartment, such as diatoms, nanoflagellates,
 picoplankton, etc.
 in the group of phytoplankton.
 The group function is in this case called 
\family typewriter
PhytoPlankton(no_of_subgroups, no_of_components)
\family default
, and allows to access the memory 
\family typewriter
P1c
\family default
 by writing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
lstparams "basicstyle={\normalsize\ttfamily}"
inline false
status open

\begin_layout LyX-Code

PhytoPlankton(iiP1,iiC)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model state variables and components are defined in the model layout
 file of each preset (Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Presets"

\end_inset

) which will be detailed in Chap.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Design-model-layout"

\end_inset

.
 It is now only sufficient to list the constants indicating the constituents,
 namely 
\family typewriter
iiC
\family default
, 
\family typewriter
iiN
\family default
, 
\family typewriter
iiP
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
iiSi
\family default
.
 For each defined group there is a named constant starting with the letters
 
\family typewriter
ii
\family default
 which holds the total number of existing subgroups (e.g.
 
\family typewriter
iiPhytoPlankton
\family default
).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A typical example of the use of groups is to compute the total amount of
 food available to microzooplankton (from 
\family typewriter
MicroZoo.F90
\family default
):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
lstparams "basicstyle={\normalsize\ttfamily},language=Fortran"
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

do i = 1 ,iiPhytoPlankton
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

    PPYc(:,i) = p_paPPY(zoo,i)*PhytoPlankton(i,iiC)* &
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

                MM_vector(PhytoPlankton(i,iiC), p_minfood(zoo))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

    rumc = rumc + PPYc(:,i)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

    rumn = rumn + PPYc(:,i)*qncPPY(i,:)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

    rump = rump + PPYc(:,i)*qpcPPY(i,:)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

 end do
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compare this code with the equation for food availability and capture efficiency
 presented in Sec.
  
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Zoo-Food-availability"

\end_inset

 of the BFM description and it will show how it is simple to cycle over
 all the phytoplankton variables, independently of the number and type of
 the defined subgroups.
\end_layout

